-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Nehemiah (Chapters 1–13)
-- 3 difficulties × 13 chapters = 208 total questions
-- kids: 3, teens: 5, adults: 8 per chapter
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 1 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 1, 'kids', 1, 'What sad news did Nehemiah hear about Jerusalem?', 'The wall was broken down and the gates were burned with fire', 'The temple had been destroyed by an earthquake', 'The people of Jerusalem had been taken captive again', 'The city had been flooded by a great river', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:3 — "The wall of Jerusalem also is broken down, and the gates thereof are burned with fire."'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'kids', 2, 'What did Nehemiah do when he heard the bad news about Jerusalem?', 'He wept, mourned, fasted, and prayed before God', 'He immediately packed his bags to travel to Jerusalem', 'He wrote a letter to the king asking for help', 'He gathered soldiers to fight the enemies', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:4 — "When I heard these words, that I sat down and wept, and mourned certain days, and fasted, and prayed before the God of heaven."'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'kids', 3, 'What was Nehemiah''s job for King Artaxerxes?', 'He was the king''s cupbearer', 'He was the king''s chief soldier', 'He was the king''s builder', 'He was the king''s scribe', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:11 — "For I was the king''s cupbearer."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 1, 'teens', 1, 'Who brought Nehemiah the report about Jerusalem''s broken walls and burned gates?', 'Hanani, one of his brethren, came with men out of Judah', 'Ezra the scribe sent a written message from Jerusalem', 'A royal messenger arrived from Artaxerxes with the news', 'Tobiah the servant sent a letter describing the state of Jerusalem', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:2 — "Hanani, one of my brethren, came, he and certain men of Judah; and I asked them concerning the Jews that had escaped, which were left of the captivity."'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'teens', 2, 'In which month and year did Nehemiah receive the news about Jerusalem?', 'The month Chisleu in the twentieth year', 'The month Nisan in the fifteenth year', 'The month Tishri in the twenty-second year', 'The month Adar in the nineteenth year', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:1 — "In the month Chisleu, in the twentieth year, as I was in Shushan the palace."'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'teens', 3, 'What attributes of God did Nehemiah acknowledge at the beginning of his prayer?', 'The great and terrible God, that keepeth covenant and mercy for them that love him and observe his commandments', 'The God of heaven who is holy and righteous and full of compassion', 'The LORD of hosts who is slow to anger and plenteous in mercy', 'The everlasting God who neither slumbers nor sleeps and knows all things', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:5 — "I beseech thee, O LORD God of heaven, the great and terrible God, that keepeth covenant and mercy for them that love him and observe his commandments."'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'teens', 4, 'What sin did Nehemiah confess on behalf of himself and his people?', 'We have dealt very corruptly against thee, and have not kept the commandments, nor the statutes, nor the judgments', 'We have forsaken the temple and not offered the required sacrifices', 'We have married foreign women and forgotten the law of Moses', 'We have not paid our tithes and have robbed God of his due', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:7 — "We have dealt very corruptly against thee, and have not kept the commandments, nor the statutes, nor the judgments, which thou commandedst thy servant Moses."'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'teens', 5, 'What promise from Moses did Nehemiah remind God of in his prayer?', 'If they returned to God and kept his commandments, he would gather them from the uttermost part of heaven to the place chosen for his name', 'God had promised to restore the walls of Jerusalem if the people repented', 'Moses had promised that Israel would never be fully destroyed among the nations', 'God had sworn to Abraham that his seed would always inherit the land of Canaan', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:9 — "But if ye turn unto me, and keep my commandments, and do them; though there were of you cast out unto the uttermost part of the heaven, yet will I gather them from thence, and will bring them unto the place that I have chosen to set my name there."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 1, 'What is the historical setting of Nehemiah 1:1 — "Shushan the palace" in the twentieth year — and who is the king in view?', 'Shushan (Susa) was the winter capital of the Persian Empire; the twentieth year refers to the reign of Artaxerxes I Longimanus (c. 445/444 BC), making Nehemiah a contemporary of Ezra', 'Shushan was Babylon''s administrative centre and the twentieth year refers to Nebuchadnezzar''s reign', 'Shushan was a provincial city of Judah and the year refers to the reign of Darius the Mede', 'The palace at Shushan was the summer residence of Cyrus the Great in whose second year Nehemiah served', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:1 — "In the month Chisleu, in the twentieth year, as I was in Shushan the palace." Artaxerxes I''s twentieth year (Neh 2:1) is the reference point; Susa was indeed the Persian royal winter residence, confirmed by the book of Esther and archaeological evidence.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 2, 'How does Nehemiah''s prayer in chapter 1 reflect the covenant theology of Deuteronomy 28-30?', 'Nehemiah confesses the curses of Deuteronomy 28 have fallen on Israel for disobedience, then appeals to the restoration promise of Deuteronomy 30 — that God will regather the scattered if they return', 'Nehemiah draws on Leviticus 26 exclusively and makes no reference to Deuteronomy''s covenant structure', 'Nehemiah cites the Abrahamic covenant rather than the Mosaic covenant as the basis for restoration', 'The prayer reflects Solomonic temple theology from 1 Kings 8 without a specific Deuteronomy connection', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:8-9 — "Remember, I beseech thee, the word that thou commandedst thy servant Moses, saying, If ye transgress, I will scatter you abroad...But if ye turn unto me...yet will I gather them." This directly echoes Deuteronomy 30:1-4''s promise of regathering after repentance following the covenant curses.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 3, 'What does Nehemiah''s identification of himself as one who "have sinned against thee: both I and my father''s house have sinned" reveal about his theology of corporate solidarity?', 'He identified himself fully with Israel''s collective guilt even as a righteous man in exile, embodying the intercessory tradition of Moses, Daniel, and Ezra who confessed national sins as their own', 'He was personally guilty of specific sins in Susa that he confessed before God', 'He was following a ritual formula that all priests used when praying for Israel', 'He included his father''s house only to establish his Israelite credentials before God', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:6 — "Confess the sins of the children of Israel, which we have sinned against thee: both I and my father''s house have sinned." Compare Daniel 9:5 — "We have sinned" and Ezra 9:6 — "I am ashamed...our iniquities are increased." This is the biblical pattern of representative repentance.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 4, 'What is the significance of Nehemiah describing the Jerusalem returnees as "in great affliction and reproach" in the context of Ezra''s earlier work?', 'Despite Ezra''s revival and the earlier return under Zerubbabel, the physical state of the city remained a reproach — the walls destroyed since 586 BC still left Jerusalem vulnerable and dishonoured among the nations', 'It indicates that Ezra''s reforms had failed completely and the people had returned to paganism', 'It refers to a new Babylonian attack that had destroyed the walls rebuilt under Zerubbabel', 'It shows that the returnees were being persecuted by Artaxerxes who had stopped temple construction', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:3 — "The remnant that are left of the captivity there in the province are in great affliction and reproach: the wall of Jerusalem also is broken down." The walls had never been rebuilt since Nebuchadnezzar''s destruction; Ezra 4:23 records a hostile order that stopped previous wall-building attempts.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 5, 'How does Nehemiah''s prayer use the title "thy servants" strategically, and what does this reveal about his approach to petitioning God?', 'He appeals to Moses (thy servant), Israel (thy servants), and himself (thy servant) as the basis for God''s action — claiming covenant relationship rather than personal merit as the ground for his petition', 'The title "servants" is simply a polite honorific with no theological weight in his prayer', 'He uses "servants" only to distinguish himself from the pagan Persians surrounding him', 'Nehemiah uses "servant" to assert his priestly status as the qualified intercessor for Israel', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:6-11 — "thy servant...thy servants the children of Israel...thy servants who desire to fear thy name...thy servant." Each use grounds the petition in relationship: God''s covenant people have a claim on his attention precisely because they are his servants.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 6, 'What does the phrase "certain days" of fasting and mourning in Nehemiah 1:4 suggest about the timeline between Chisleu (November/December) and Nisan (March/April) mentioned in Nehemiah 2:1?', 'It indicates approximately four months of sustained intercession before Nehemiah acted, showing that his eventual request to the king was preceded by prolonged prayer rather than impulsive action', 'It means only a few days passed before Nehemiah immediately approached the king', 'The "certain days" were a fixed annual fast on the Hebrew calendar for Jerusalem''s fall', 'Nehemiah was legally required to fast for exactly thirty days before petitioning a Persian monarch', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:1 — "month Chisleu, in the twentieth year" and Nehemiah 2:1 — "month Nisan, in the twentieth year." The gap is roughly four months. Nehemiah 1:4 — "I sat down and wept, and mourned certain days, and fasted, and prayed" — suggests this entire period was spent in intercession.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 7, 'How does Nehemiah''s final petition — "prosper, I pray thee, thy servant this day, and grant him mercy in the sight of this man" (Neh 1:11) — set up the narrative of chapter 2?', 'The prayer explicitly anticipates Nehemiah''s request to the king; "this man" is Artaxerxes, and the petition for "mercy" (rachamim) prepares theologically for Artaxerxes'' gracious response in chapter 2', 'The petition is for a safe journey to Jerusalem and has no connection to chapter 2''s audience', '"This man" refers to Hanani, who Nehemiah hoped would carry a petition back to Jerusalem on his behalf', 'The petition is for God to soften Tobiah''s heart so the rebuilding could proceed without opposition', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:11 — "grant him mercy in the sight of this man. For I was the king''s cupbearer." This prayer is answered in Nehemiah 2:8 — "the king granted me, according to the good hand of my God upon me." The chapter 1 prayer and chapter 2 answer form a deliberate literary bracket.'),
('Nehemiah', 1, 'adults', 8, 'What does Nehemiah''s prayer structure — adoration, confession, Scripture appeal, and supplication — model about intercessory prayer, and how does it compare to Daniel''s prayer in Daniel 9?', 'Both prayers follow the same structure: acknowledging God''s covenant character, confessing national sin, appealing to God''s own promises, and making a specific petition — showing a consistent biblical pattern of covenant intercession', 'Nehemiah''s prayer is primarily personal while Daniel''s is entirely national with no personal confession', 'Daniel''s prayer in chapter 9 emphasises God''s righteousness while Nehemiah''s focuses on God''s power — they are theologically distinct', 'The two prayers share only the confession element; their petitions and theological bases are entirely different', 'a', 'Nehemiah 1:5-11 and Daniel 9:4-19 both: open with "O LORD, the great and dreadful God, keeping the covenant" (Neh 1:5; Dan 9:4), confess Israel''s sin (Neh 1:6-7; Dan 9:5-11), appeal to Mosaic warnings (Neh 1:8; Dan 9:11-13), and close with a specific petition grounded in God''s name and mercy (Neh 1:11; Dan 9:19).');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 2 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 2, 'kids', 1, 'Why did the king notice that Nehemiah was sad?', 'Nehemiah''s face was sad because he was sorrowful in his heart', 'Nehemiah had been crying all morning in front of the king', 'Nehemiah had torn his clothes as a sign of mourning', 'Nehemiah had refused to eat the king''s food for three days', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:2 — "The king said unto me, Why is thy countenance sad, seeing thou art not sick? this is nothing else but sorrow of heart."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'kids', 2, 'What did Nehemiah ask the king to let him do?', 'Send him to Judah to rebuild the city where his fathers were buried', 'Allow him to write a letter to the people of Jerusalem', 'Give him soldiers to guard the city of Jerusalem', 'Let him take a group of priests back to Jerusalem', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:5 — "I said unto the king, If it please the king, and if thy servant have found favour in thy sight, that thou wouldest send me unto Judah, unto the city of my fathers'' sepulchres, that I may build it."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'kids', 3, 'What did Nehemiah say after the king agreed to help him build Jerusalem?', 'So the king granted me, according to the good hand of my God upon me', 'Nehemiah shouted for joy and ran to tell his friends', 'He knelt before the king and gave thanks immediately', 'He said that God had opened the king''s heart as he had prayed', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:8 — "The king granted me, according to the good hand of my God upon me."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 2, 'teens', 1, 'What did Nehemiah do silently before answering the king''s question about why he was sad?', 'He prayed to the God of heaven', 'He took a deep breath and steadied himself', 'He thought carefully about what the law allowed him to say', 'He glanced at the queen who gave him a nod of encouragement', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:4 — "Then the king said unto me, For what dost thou make request? So I prayed to the God of heaven."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'teens', 2, 'What letters did Nehemiah ask the king to provide for his journey to Jerusalem?', 'Letters to the governors beyond the river for safe passage, and a letter to Asaph keeper of the forest for timber', 'A royal decree granting him authority over all of Judah and Samaria', 'A letter to the high priest authorising him to use the temple treasury', 'A royal seal to show all the people that he was the king''s representative', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:7-8 — "Let letters be given me to the governors beyond the river, that they may convey me over till I come into Judah; And a letter unto Asaph the keeper of the king''s forest, that he may give me timber."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'teens', 3, 'Who were the two main enemies who were very grieved when they heard Nehemiah had come to seek the welfare of the children of Israel?', 'Sanballat the Horonite and Tobiah the servant, the Ammonite', 'Geshem the Arabian and Tobiah the Ammonite', 'Sanballat the Samaritan and Geshem the Persian', 'Eliashib the priest and Tobiah the official from Samaria', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:10 — "When Sanballat the Horonite, and Tobiah the servant, the Ammonite, heard of it, it grieved them exceedingly that there was come a man to seek the welfare of the children of Israel."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'teens', 4, 'How did Nehemiah inspect the walls of Jerusalem without telling anyone his plans?', 'He went out by night with a few men and viewed the broken walls and burned gates secretly', 'He sent trusted servants ahead of him to report on the state of the walls', 'He disguised himself as a merchant and walked through the city in daylight', 'He climbed a hill outside the city and surveyed the damage from a distance', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:12-13 — "I arose in the night, I and some few men with me; neither told I any man what my God had put in my heart to do at Jerusalem...And I went out by night by the gate of the valley."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'teens', 5, 'What faith-filled declaration did Nehemiah make to the people when he called them to rebuild?', 'The God of heaven, he will prosper us; therefore we his servants will arise and build', 'The LORD our God is able to give us victory over all our enemies if we trust in him', 'Fear not for God is with us and no weapon formed against Jerusalem shall prosper', 'The hand of God is mighty and he has already promised that these walls shall rise again', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:20 — "The God of heaven, he will prosper us; therefore we his servants will arise and build."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 1, 'What does the phrase "I was afraid" in Nehemiah 2:2 reveal about the dangers of Nehemiah''s situation in the Persian court?', 'Showing sadness before the king could be interpreted as ingratitude or even disloyalty — a capital offence in Persian court etiquette — making Nehemiah''s petition genuinely dangerous', 'Nehemiah was afraid the king would refuse his request and he would be embarrassed', 'Persian protocol required cupbearers never to speak unless spoken to, so any speech was frightening', 'Nehemiah feared that Sanballat had already informed the king against him', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:2 — "Then I was very sore afraid." Esther 4:11 confirms that approaching the king unbidden was punishable by death; expressing personal sorrow in the royal presence could similarly be viewed as an affront to the king''s provision, making Nehemiah''s honest response a genuine act of courage.'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 2, 'What is the significance of the queen sitting beside the king during Nehemiah''s audience in Nehemiah 2:6?', 'The detail is unique — Persian queens rarely appeared at official audiences; some scholars suggest the queen''s presence (possibly Damaspia) may have created a sympathetic atmosphere that aided Nehemiah''s request', 'The queen''s presence was required by Persian law for all requests involving foreign provinces', 'The mention of the queen proves this was an informal private dinner rather than an official audience', 'It indicates the queen had been lobbying on Nehemiah''s behalf prior to this conversation', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:6 — "And the king said unto me, (the queen also sitting by him)." This parenthetical is the only mention of the queen in the book. Greek historians note Persian queens were normally secluded; the detail appears to be an eyewitness observation by Nehemiah himself.'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 3, 'What does Nehemiah''s night inspection of the walls reveal about his leadership method before the public announcement in Nehemiah 2:17?', 'He gathered precise intelligence about the actual state of the ruins before making any public commitment, demonstrating that his faith declaration was grounded in careful prior assessment rather than naive enthusiasm', 'The night inspection was legally required before any building project could be announced in Judah', 'Nehemiah inspected at night to avoid Sanballat''s spies who might report to the Persian governor', 'He was following the advice of the elders who told him to assess the damage before speaking', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:12,16-17 — "neither told I any man what my God had put in my heart...And the rulers knew not whither I went, or what I did...Then said I unto them, Ye see the distress that we are in." Nehemiah''s prior covert assessment gave his call to action credibility grounded in reality.'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 4, 'How does Nehemiah''s response to Sanballat and Tobiah''s accusation of rebellion in Nehemiah 2:20 differ from a defensive denial, and what is its theological character?', 'Rather than arguing his legal right, Nehemiah anchors his answer in theology — "the God of heaven will prosper us" — turning a political accusation into a declaration of divine purpose that simultaneously excludes the opponents from any share in Jerusalem', 'Nehemiah produces his royal letters as legal proof that he is not rebelling against Artaxerxes', 'Nehemiah ignores the accusation and changes the subject to focus on practical building plans', 'He appeals to the elders of Judah to testify that the project was approved by the whole community', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:20 — "The God of heaven, he will prosper us; therefore we his servants will arise and build: but ye have no portion, nor right, nor memorial, in Jerusalem." The three-fold exclusion — no portion, no right, no memorial — is a comprehensive legal and theological rejection.'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 5, 'What does the specific routing of Nehemiah''s night ride — Valley Gate, Dung Gate, Fountain Gate, King''s Pool, Brook Kidron — tell us about the historical geography of Jerusalem?', 'It traces the southern and eastern circuit of the city walls, indicating Nehemiah began at the southwest (Valley Gate) and rode along the southern and southeastern walls, being blocked at the Kidron by rubble', 'It shows Nehemiah inspected only the northern wall since that was where Sanballat''s attack was expected', 'The route circles the entire perimeter of the city in a single continuous sweep without obstruction', 'It indicates Nehemiah started at the eastern gate and moved west, ending at the original city of David', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:13-15 — "I went out by night by the gate of the valley...and viewed the walls of Jerusalem...turned back and entered by the gate of the valley...the brook that goeth through the midst." Archaeologists have confirmed this route around the southern Ophel ridge where the densest rubble from 586 BC was found.'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 6, 'What rhetorical strategy does Nehemiah use in Nehemiah 2:17-18 to motivate the people, and how does he counter the "we cannot do this" mentality?', 'He first names the shared problem honestly ("ye see the distress"), then grounds the call to action in God''s hand upon him and the king''s word — replacing personal inadequacy with divine provision and royal authority as the twin pillars of motivation', 'He appeals to national pride by reminding them that their ancestors built the original walls under Solomon', 'He promises royal wages and military protection to anyone who joins the building project', 'He uses shame, pointing out that the surrounding nations are mocking them for living in ruined walls', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:17-18 — "Then said I unto them, Ye see the distress that we are in...come, and let us build up the wall of Jerusalem, that we be no more a reproach. Then I told them of the hand of my God which was good upon me; as also the king''s words that he had spoken unto me."'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 7, 'What is the significance of Sanballat being identified as "the Horonite" and Tobiah as "the Ammonite servant" in terms of their opposition to Jerusalem''s restoration?', 'Sanballat was likely from Beth-horon in Samaria (a mixed-religion province) while Tobiah was an Ammonite official — both represented neighbouring peoples who had geopolitical interests in keeping Judah weak and had no legitimate claim to Jerusalem', 'The titles indicate they were hired administrators working for the Persian crown who opposed Jerusalem on official Persian orders', '"Horonite" and "Ammonite" are derogatory epithets invented by Nehemiah to discredit legitimate opposition from fellow Israelites', 'Both titles indicate priestly lineages that felt threatened by Nehemiah''s new religious authority in Jerusalem', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:10,19 — "Sanballat the Horonite, and Tobiah the servant, the Ammonite...and Geshem the Arabian." The Elephantine Papyri mention Sanballat as governor of Samaria, confirming his historical existence. An Ammonite official controlling Transjordan had direct interest in preventing a strong Jerusalem.'),
('Nehemiah', 2, 'adults', 8, 'How does the phrase "the good hand of my God was upon me" (Neh 2:8,18) function as a theological motif connecting Nehemiah to the Ezra narrative?', 'The identical phrase "the good hand of his God upon him" appears in Ezra 7:9; 8:18 — it is a signature expression of divine providence over the entire Ezra-Nehemiah restoration project, linking both leaders under the same theological framework', 'The phrase is a standard blessing formula used by all Persian Jews and carries no special link to Ezra', 'Nehemiah coined the phrase independently as his personal motto without any connection to Ezra''s writings', 'The phrase appears only in Nehemiah and never in Ezra, making any literary connection coincidental', 'a', 'Nehemiah 2:8 — "the good hand of my God upon me" and Nehemiah 2:18 — "the hand of my God which was good upon me." Compare Ezra 7:9 — "the good hand of his God upon him" and Ezra 8:18 — "by the good hand of our God upon us." The shared phrase ties the two books together as one unified restoration narrative.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 3 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 3, 'kids', 1, 'Which gate did Eliashib the high priest and his fellow priests begin rebuilding?', 'The Sheep Gate', 'The Fish Gate', 'The Horse Gate', 'The Water Gate', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:1 — "Then Eliashib the high priest rose up with his brethren the priests, and they builded the sheep gate."'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'kids', 2, 'What group of people refused to help with the work and would not put their shoulders to the task?', 'The nobles of the Tekoites', 'The merchants of Jerusalem', 'The men of Jericho', 'The Levites in the city', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:5 — "The Tekoites repaired; but their nobles put not their necks to the work of their Lord."'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'kids', 3, 'What did many of the builders repair — a section next to their own homes?', 'The piece over against their own houses', 'The wall next to the city market', 'The gate beside the temple courts', 'The tower near the palace gardens', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:28-30 — Several workers repaired "over against his house." For example, v.28: "From above the horse gate repaired the priests, every one over against his house."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 3, 'teens', 1, 'What two towers did Eliashib and the priests sanctify when they built the Sheep Gate?', 'The tower of Meah and the tower of Hananeel', 'The tower of David and the tower of Siloam', 'The furnace tower and the tower of the ovens', 'The tower of Babel and the tower at the corner', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:1 — "They builded the sheep gate; they sanctified it, and set up the doors of it; even unto the tower of Meah they sanctified it, unto the tower of Hananeel."'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'teens', 2, 'What craftsmen repaired the Old Gate according to Nehemiah 3:6?', 'Jehoiada the son of Paseah, and Meshullam the son of Besodeiah', 'Uzziel the son of Harhaiah of the goldsmiths', 'Shallum the son of Halohesh, ruler of half Jerusalem', 'Hanun and the inhabitants of Zanoah', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:6 — "Moreover the old gate repaired Jehoiada the son of Paseah, and Meshullam the son of Besodeiah; they laid the beams thereof, and set up the doors thereof, and the locks thereof, and the bars thereof."'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'teens', 3, 'What is notable about Shallum the son of Halohesh who repaired a section of the wall?', 'He was ruler of half part of Jerusalem and repaired the wall with the help of his daughters', 'He was the chief priest who repaired the section nearest to the temple', 'He was a Levite who worked without pay and was honoured above the others', 'He was the only man from outside Judah who came to help with the building', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:12 — "And next unto him repaired Shallum the son of Halohesh, the ruler of the half part of Jerusalem, he and his daughters."'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'teens', 4, 'Who repaired the Dung Gate, and how much of it did he repair?', 'Malchiah the son of Rechab, ruler of part of Beth-haccerem — the whole gate', 'Hanun and the inhabitants of Zanoah — half the gate', 'Rephaiah the son of Hur — one hundred cubits of wall by the gate', 'Nehemiah himself, because no other man would take that section', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:14 — "But the dung gate repaired Malchiah the son of Rechab, the ruler of part of Beth-haccerem; he built it, and set up the doors thereof, the locks thereof, and the bars thereof."'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'teens', 5, 'What guild or profession of craftsmen repaired the wall from the great tower to the sheep gate?', 'The goldsmiths and the merchants', 'The priests and Levites together', 'The sons of the carpenters guild', 'The Nethinims who lived in Ophel', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:31-32 — "After him repaired Malchiah the goldsmith''s son...The goldsmiths and the merchants repaired" (v.32). Nehemiah 3:22,26 also notes priests and Nethinims in nearby sections.'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 1, 'What is the literary and administrative significance of Nehemiah 3''s detailed register of builders and sections?', 'It functions as an official record authenticating the work, distributing civic responsibility across all social classes and districts, and demonstrating the unified community effort — priests, Levites, merchants, rulers, and common people all participating', 'It is primarily a genealogical document establishing who had the right to live within the rebuilt walls', 'The register was a Persian administrative requirement for any construction project on royal land', 'It was compiled after the fact by Ezra the scribe and inserted into Nehemiah''s memoir', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3 lists high priest (v.1), district rulers (vv.9,12,14-19), Levites (v.17), goldsmiths (v.8,31), merchants (v.32), and ordinary families — across at least ten administrative districts of Judah. The breadth demonstrates that the rebuilding was a whole-community covenant act.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 2, 'What does the note that the Tekoite nobles "put not their necks to the work of their Lord" (Neh 3:5) reveal about social tensions in the restoration community, and how does it contrast with the broader Tekoite participation?', 'The nobles'' refusal shows class-based resistance, while the ordinary Tekoites not only worked their own section but "repaired another piece" (v.27) — illustrating that social rank was no guarantee of covenant faithfulness', 'The nobles were exempt by law from manual labour and their absence was expected and acceptable', 'The Tekoite nobles had a legitimate exemption because they were managing regional defence during the build', 'The passage indicates the Tekoites as a whole refused and only a minority participated', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:5 — "their nobles put not their necks to the work of their Lord" contrasted with v.27 — "After them the Tekoites repaired another piece." The same family group produced both shirkers and double-workers, making the social contrast within one community especially pointed.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological significance of the high priest Eliashib leading the wall-building in Nehemiah 3:1, given that the work was civic rather than specifically religious?', 'It demonstrates that in the post-exilic theocracy, the distinction between sacred and civic was collapsed — rebuilding Jerusalem''s walls was itself a holy act, and priestly involvement from the outset consecrated the entire enterprise', 'Eliashib led because he owned land adjacent to the Sheep Gate and had a financial interest in its repair', 'Priestly leadership was mandated by the Torah for any large construction project involving the city of God', 'Eliashib''s participation was politically motivated to ensure the priesthood had influence over the rebuilt city', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:1 — "Eliashib the high priest...builded the sheep gate; they sanctified it." The verb "sanctified" (vayekaddeshuhu) applied to the gate signals that the entire rebuilding project was understood as sacred work — consistent with Nehemiah 2:20 where God''s servants build God''s city.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 4, 'How does the structure of Nehemiah 3 — starting and ending at the Sheep Gate — reflect ancient city administration and symbolism?', 'The circuit begins and ends at the Sheep Gate (vv.1,32) forming a literary and spatial circle, symbolising the completeness of the community''s work and the integrity of the restored city perimeter', 'The Sheep Gate was chosen as start and finish because it was the largest and most damaged section', 'The circuit began at the Sheep Gate because it was the closest to the Persian governor''s residence', 'The Sheep Gate appears at both ends only because the chapter was compiled from two separate lists', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:1 — "they builded the sheep gate" and 3:32 — "the goldsmiths and the merchants repaired" completing the circle back to the Sheep Gate. The ring structure mirrors the physical circuit of the city walls, with the sacred Sheep Gate (through which temple sacrifices passed) as the theological anchor of the whole project.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 5, 'What does the repeated phrase "next unto him" (or "after him") throughout Nehemiah 3 reveal about the project''s organisational method?', 'It reveals a contiguous assignment system where each group''s section joined seamlessly to the next — a practical coordination strategy that eliminated gaps while distributing ownership and accountability section by section', 'The phrase is a scribal formula indicating that each worker voluntarily chose to stand beside a neighbour', 'It indicates workers were ranked by social standing, with each group assigned based on their position in the hierarchy', 'The phrase simply means workers arrived at the site in sequence and has no organisational significance', 'a', 'The phrase "next unto him" or "after him" appears approximately 30 times in Nehemiah 3 (vv.2,4,5,7,8,9,10 etc.), creating an interlocking chain of responsibility around the full perimeter. This ensured full coverage with clear accountability while building community solidarity through shared physical proximity.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 6, 'What does the phrase "over against his house" (Nehemiah 3:10,23,28-30) suggest about Nehemiah''s motivation strategy for the builders?', 'Assigning builders to the section nearest their own homes gave them a personal stake in quality and completion — they were literally defending their own families — making it both practical and motivationally wise', 'It indicates that only homeowners were permitted to participate in the building project', 'The phrase shows workers were compensated in land grants adjacent to their building sections', 'Builders worked near their homes because Persian law required workers to stay within their registered district', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:23 — "After him repaired Benjamin and Hashub over against their house. After him repaired Azariah...by his house." Nehemiah''s assignment of family sections near homes is a practical insight: workers with the highest personal stake in a section''s integrity will build most carefully.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 7, 'How does Nehemiah 3 function in the overall structure of the book as a counterweight to the opposition listed in chapters 4 and 6?', 'Chapter 3 establishes the breadth and unity of participation before chapters 4-6 introduce external and internal threats — showing that the community''s solidarity was the foundation that made resistance to opposition possible', 'Chapter 3 is a pause in the narrative that has no structural relationship to the opposition accounts', 'Chapter 3 was placed here by an editor to lengthen the book before the dramatic conflict sections', 'Chapter 3 functions as a legal document and was not part of Nehemiah''s original memoir', 'a', 'The register of unified community effort in ch.3 creates dramatic contrast with Sanballat''s mockery in ch.4:2-3. The breadth of participation — 40+ named individuals from all walks of life — makes the subsequent opposition appear to be fighting not just Nehemiah but the whole reconstituted community of God''s people.'),
('Nehemiah', 3, 'adults', 8, 'What can be deduced about the administrative geography of post-exilic Judah from the district rulers (rulers of half-districts) mentioned in Nehemiah 3?', 'Nehemiah 3 reveals that Judah was divided into at least ten administrative sub-districts, each with a ruler responsible for his population''s section of the wall — indicating a functioning civil administration organised perhaps by Artaxerxes'' provincial system', 'The rulers mentioned were simply wealthy landowners with no official Persian administrative standing', 'The districts were purely ecclesiastical and the rulers were all priests serving temple jurisdictions', 'Post-exilic Judah had no administrative structure; the rulers were self-appointed community leaders', 'a', 'Nehemiah 3:9 — "Rephaiah the son of Hur, the ruler of the half part of Jerusalem"; v.12 — "Shallum...ruler of the half part of Jerusalem"; v.14 — "Malchiah...ruler of part of Beth-haccerem"; v.15 — "Shallun...ruler of part of Mizpah"; v.17-19 include rulers of Keilah parts. Together these indicate a Persian-organised provincial system with Judah subdivided into administrative units.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 4 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 4, 'kids', 1, 'What did Sanballat and Tobiah do when they heard the Jews were rebuilding the wall?', 'They mocked and made fun of the builders', 'They attacked Jerusalem with an army', 'They sent a letter to the king of Persia', 'They bribed the workers to stop building', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:1 — "When Sanballat heard that we builded the wall, he was wroth, and took great indignation, and mocked the Jews."'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'kids', 2, 'What did the builders carry in one hand while they worked on the wall?', 'A sword while doing the work with the other hand', 'A torch to see where they were building', 'A water jar to keep cool in the heat', 'A hammer to drive the stakes into the ground', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:17 — "They which builded on the wall, and they that bare burdens, with those that laded, every one with one of his hands wrought in the work, and with the other hand held a weapon."'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'kids', 3, 'What did Nehemiah tell the people not to be afraid of, and whom did he tell them to remember?', 'Remember the LORD which is great and terrible, and fight for your brethren', 'Fear not the armies of Sanballat for the angels will protect you', 'Do not be afraid because the king of Persia has sent soldiers to help', 'Remember that the walls were built by your ancestors and God will defend them', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:14 — "Be not ye afraid of them: remember the Lord, which is great and terrible, and fight for your brethren, your sons, and your daughters, your wives, and your houses."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 4, 'teens', 1, 'What mocking question did Tobiah add about the wall the Jews were building?', 'Even that which they build, if a fox go up, he shall even break down their stone wall', 'Do they think they can rebuild in one day what took Solomon years to build?', 'Will these feeble Jews make their burnt stones live again out of the heaps of rubbish?', 'Can stones pulled from a rubbish heap become a wall that will last a generation?', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:3 — "Now Tobiah the Ammonite was by him, and he said, Even that which they build, if a fox go up, he shall even break down their stone wall."'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'teens', 2, 'What prayer did Nehemiah pray in response to the mockery of Sanballat and Tobiah?', 'Hear, O our God; for we are despised: and turn their reproach upon their own head', 'O LORD arise and scatter thine enemies and let thy people build in peace', 'Let not our enemies triumph LORD but give us strength to finish this work', 'Hear us O God and repay our enemies sevenfold for their contempt', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:4 — "Hear, O our God; for we are despised: and turn their reproach upon their own head, and give them for a prey in the land of captivity."'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'teens', 3, 'What was the conspirators'' plan according to Nehemiah 4:11?', 'They said they would come in among the builders and kill them and cause the work to cease', 'They planned to flood the construction site to make the foundations unstable', 'They intended to steal the building materials at night and scatter them', 'They planned to convince the Persian governor to send an order stopping the work', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:11 — "Our adversaries said, They shall not know, neither see, till we come in the midst among them, and slay them, and cause the work to cease."'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'teens', 4, 'What two things did Nehemiah set behind the wall when the threat of attack became clear?', 'He set the people after the wall by families with their swords, spears, and bows', 'He stationed soldiers at the top of the wall and archers at the gates', 'He placed half the men to guard and half to build as shifts throughout the night', 'He positioned the cavalry outside the wall and the foot soldiers inside', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:13 — "I even set the people after the lower places behind the wall, and on the higher places, I even set the people after their families with their swords, their spears, and their bows."'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'teens', 5, 'What practical signal did Nehemiah set up so that scattered workers could quickly come together when threatened?', 'A trumpeter who would sound the trumpet so all could rally to that place', 'A system of fire beacons on the towers that could be seen across the city', 'A runner who would carry the alarm from gate to gate around the wall', 'A bell hung at the highest point of the wall that could be heard citywide', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:18,20 — "He that sounded the trumpet was by me...In what place therefore ye hear the sound of the trumpet, resort ye thither unto us: our God shall fight for us."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 1, 'What is the rhetorical structure of Sanballat''s mockery in Nehemiah 4:2-3, and how does it function as a psychological warfare tactic?', 'Sanballat speaks before an audience (army of Samaria) using five rhetorical questions that ridicule the Jews'' feebleness, resources, time, and building quality — designed to demoralise the workers through public shame rather than direct confrontation', 'Sanballat''s mockery is a formal legal protest lodged with the Persian governor against unlicensed construction', 'The speech is a private letter to Tobiah and was not intended to be heard by the builders', 'Sanballat is making a military assessment of Jerusalem''s defences rather than personal mockery', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:2 — "What do these feeble Jews? will they fortify themselves? will they sacrifice? will they make an end in a day? will they revive the stones out of the heaps of the rubbish?" Five questions + Tobiah''s fox-comment (v.3) constitute a coordinated public ridicule campaign designed to crush morale before any military action.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 2, 'How does Nehemiah''s prayer in Nehemiah 4:4-5 — invoking God''s judgment on the mockers — relate to the imprecatory psalms, and is it theologically problematic?', 'The prayer stands in the tradition of imprecatory psalms (Pss 58, 69, 137) — calling on God as righteous judge to vindicate his people and honour; it is not personal revenge but covenant theology, appealing to God''s own honour being reproached', 'The prayer is theologically problematic because it contradicts Jesus''s command to bless enemies and pray for persecutors', 'Nehemiah''s prayer is a formal legal petition rather than a religious prayer and has no connection to the Psalms', 'The prayer is simply an expression of frustration and is not meant to be taken as a model for prayer', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:4-5 — "turn their reproach upon their own head...cover not their iniquity." Compare Psalm 69:27-28; 137:7-9. The context makes clear this is not petty revenge: the enemies are opposing God''s work and reproaching God''s people — the appeal is to God''s covenant justice.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 3, 'What does Nehemiah 4:6 — "the people had a mind to work" — suggest as the key human factor in the project''s success against discouragement?', 'Internal motivation (lev la''am la''asot) — literally "the people''s heart was in the work" — meant that mockery failed to break their will; motivation rooted in purpose rather than wage-labour proved resilient against psychological attack', 'The people worked harder because Nehemiah threatened punishment for those who slowed down', 'The success was purely miraculous with no human factor — God caused them to continue despite their own discouragement', 'The people were unaware of the mockery and so it had no effect on their productivity', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:6 — "So built we the wall; and all the wall was joined together unto the half thereof: for the people had a mind to work." The Hebrew lev ha''am la''asot ("the heart of the people to do the work") emphasises that inner conviction, not external compulsion, drove progress even under threat.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 4, 'How does Nehemiah''s tactical reorganisation in Nehemiah 4:13-23 balance the competing demands of security and construction productivity?', 'He divided the workforce into armed guards and builders, stationed families together for motivation, used a central trumpet signal for rapid redeployment, and kept workers armed even while building — maintaining both progress and defence simultaneously', 'He stopped all construction until the threat was fully neutralised, resuming only after a peace agreement with Sanballat', 'He asked the Persian governor for a military garrison to guard the workers while they built', 'He built only at night when enemies could not see the progress and rested during the day', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:16-18 — "half of my servants wrought in the work, and the other half of them held both the spears, the shields, and the bows...every one with one of his hands wrought in the work, and with the other hand held a weapon." The strategy maintained continuous construction rather than suspending it.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 5, 'What does Nehemiah 4:10 — "the strength of the bearers of burdens is decayed, and there is much rubbish" — reveal about the internal challenges alongside the external threats?', 'It reveals that physical exhaustion and the overwhelming volume of debris were demoralising the workers — the project faced a two-front battle: enemy threats outside and worker fatigue and despair inside', 'It is a complaint from the nobles who wanted to stop work and refers to the nobles of Tekoa', 'The verse indicates a structural problem where the rubble was undermining the new foundations', 'It shows that the workers were protesting unfair labour conditions and threatening to strike', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:10 — "Judah said, The strength of the bearers of burdens is decayed, and there is much rubbish; so that we are not able to build the wall." This internal discouragement (ch.4) and the economic grievance (ch.5) form a pattern: every advance in the project faced both external opposition and internal crisis.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 6, 'What is the theological significance of Nehemiah''s declaration in Nehemiah 4:20 — "our God shall fight for us" — in the context of holy war theology?', 'It invokes the Deuteronomy 1:30; 3:22 promise that the LORD fights for Israel, reapplying the conquest-era theology to the restoration — the rebuilt wall is framed as a holy war victory where God is the true combatant', 'The declaration is purely motivational rhetoric with no connection to Torah holy war traditions', 'Nehemiah is claiming a new prophetic revelation rather than applying existing covenant promises', 'The phrase means only that God will bless their military efforts, not that God fights supernaturally on their behalf', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:20 — "our God shall fight for us." Compare Deuteronomy 1:30 — "The LORD your God which goeth before you, he shall fight for you"; Deuteronomy 3:22 — "the LORD your God he shall fight for them." Nehemiah consciously places the wall-building in the tradition of divine warfare.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 7, 'How does the detail that workers neither changed their clothes nor put away their weapons even to wash in Nehemiah 4:23 function literarily?', 'It is a vivid eyewitness detail conveying the intensity of the crisis and authenticating the memoir''s first-person character — Nehemiah himself shared these conditions, creating a solidarity between leader and worker that the narrative highlights', 'The detail indicates a specific Mosaic law about ritual cleanliness during warfare that Nehemiah was observing', 'It is a hyperbolic exaggeration intended to impress the Persian court with the severity of the threat', 'The detail was added by a later editor to make the account more dramatic', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:23 — "So neither I, nor my brethren, nor my servants, nor the men of the guard which followed me, none of us put off our clothes, saving that every one put them off for washing." The inclusion of Nehemiah himself ("neither I") demonstrates shared hardship — the mark of authentic leadership memoir.'),
('Nehemiah', 4, 'adults', 8, 'How does the account of chapter 4 illustrate the principle of "pray and act" as a biblical model for responding to threats?', 'Nehemiah prays (v.4-5,9) and immediately implements practical security measures (vv.13-23) — the two responses are complementary rather than alternatives, modelling that faith and human prudence operate together in covenant living', 'The chapter teaches that prayer alone is sufficient and that military preparations showed a lack of trust in God', 'Nehemiah''s practical measures indicate that prayer had failed and he was now relying on human strength', 'The chapter separates sacred responses (prayer) from secular responses (defence) with no theological integration', 'a', 'Nehemiah 4:9 — "we made our prayer unto our God, and set a watch against them day and night." The conjunction "and" is theologically significant: prayer and watchfulness are presented as the unified response of covenant faithfulness. This mirrors the New Testament principle of Philippians 4:6 — prayer in everything — combined with practical wisdom.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 5 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 5, 'kids', 1, 'What were the poor people of Jerusalem complaining about?', 'They had mortgaged their lands and houses and some had sold their children as servants to pay debts', 'They had not received enough food from the temple storehouses', 'The rich men had stolen their tools so they could not work on the wall', 'They were being forced to work on the wall without any pay', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:2-5 — "We...have mortgaged our lands...yea, we bring into bondage our sons and our daughters."'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'kids', 2, 'What did Nehemiah do when he heard the people''s cries about usury and debt?', 'He was very angry and rebuked the nobles and rulers who were charging interest', 'He called a fast and prayed for three days before responding', 'He went to the king of Persia and asked for extra grain', 'He told the people to be patient and wait until the wall was finished', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:6-7 — "I was very angry when I heard their cry and these words. Then I consulted with myself, and I rebuked the nobles, and the rulers."'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'kids', 3, 'What did Nehemiah give to the people as their governor without asking for pay?', 'He provided food from his own table for one hundred and fifty Jews and rulers every day', 'He gave each family a portion of land from the royal treasury', 'He distributed silver from his own wages to pay everyone''s debts', 'He provided free timber from the forest to build new homes', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:17-18 — "Moreover there were at my table an hundred and fifty of the Jews and rulers, beside those that came unto us from among the heathen."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 5, 'teens', 1, 'What three specific grievances did the people raise against their fellow Jews in Nehemiah 5:2-4?', 'They needed grain to eat, their fields were mortgaged, and they had borrowed money to pay the king''s tribute', 'They had been sold as slaves to Babylonians, their land was seized by soldiers, and they were taxed by Sanballat', 'Their wages were withheld, their children were taken as collateral, and their crops had been burned', 'The nobles charged rent on their own land, doubled the king''s tax, and refused to sell grain in a famine', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:2-4 — "We...have need of corn...We have mortgaged our lands...We have borrowed money for the king''s tribute."'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'teens', 2, 'What did Nehemiah condemn as forbidden under the law that the nobles and rulers were doing?', 'Exacting usury, every one of his brother — charging interest on loans to fellow Jews', 'Taking land from those who could not pay their tithes', 'Selling fellow Israelites to foreign masters', 'Forcing widows and orphans to work without wages', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:7 — "Ye exact usury, every one of his brother." Leviticus 25:36-37 and Deuteronomy 23:19-20 forbid charging interest to a fellow Israelite.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'teens', 3, 'What dramatic action did Nehemiah use to illustrate the curse on those who broke their promise to restore lands and stop usury?', 'He shook out his lap and said, So God shake out every man from his house who performeth not this promise', 'He tore his garment in two and called the priests to witness his vow', 'He poured water on the ground and said, Let God pour out his wrath on the covenant-breaker', 'He broke a clay pot before the assembly to symbolise what God would do to the unfaithful', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:13 — "Also I shook my lap, and said, So God shake out every man from his house, and from his labour, that performeth not this promise, even thus be he shaken out, and emptied."'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'teens', 4, 'What did the congregation say and do when Nehemiah made the nobles swear to restore everything?', 'All the congregation said Amen and praised the LORD and the people did according to this promise', 'The nobles wept and immediately returned everyone''s property on the spot', 'The priests came forward and recorded the names of all who made the promise', 'The people were silent for a moment and then broke out in singing', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:13 — "And all the congregation said, Amen, and praised the LORD. And the people did according to this promise."'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'teens', 5, 'How did Nehemiah describe the behaviour of former governors compared to his own conduct?', 'The former governors had been chargeable to the people and taken bread and wine and forty shekels of silver from them; Nehemiah did not do so because of the fear of God', 'Previous governors had been kind but Nehemiah worked the people harder because of the urgency of the building', 'Former governors never helped the poor while Nehemiah distributed food from the royal supply', 'Previous leaders charged double taxes while Nehemiah reduced taxes to zero for the duration of the building', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:15 — "But the former governors that had been before me were chargeable unto the people, and had taken of them bread and wine, beside forty shekels of silver; yea, even their servants bare rule over the people: but so did not I, because of the fear of God."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 1, 'How does the economic crisis of Nehemiah 5 expose the structural injustice within the post-exilic community, and what does it reveal about the social composition of the returnees?', 'The crisis reveals a class divide: wealthy nobles and rulers (who owned capital) exploited their poorer compatriots (who needed to borrow grain and money) even while both groups were engaged in the communal wall-building project', 'The crisis was caused entirely by the Persian tribute demand and the nobles were acting as tax collectors under royal orders', 'The poor had borrowed recklessly and the nobles were within their legal rights under Persian law', 'The crisis was a one-time famine emergency with no underlying structural injustice', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:1-5 — Three waves of complaint: food shortage (v.2), land mortgaged (v.3), royal tribute forcing loans (v.4). The result in v.5 — "we bring into bondage our sons and daughters" — shows debt-slavery developing within the covenant community during the very period of national renewal.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 2, 'What Mosaic law did Nehemiah cite as the basis for his condemnation of usury among the returnees, and how did he frame his appeal to the nobles?', 'He appealed to the prohibition of charging interest to fellow Israelites (Leviticus 25:35-37; Deuteronomy 23:19-20), framing the nobles'' action as a violation of covenant brotherhood that nullified the redemptive purpose of the return from exile', 'Nehemiah cited the jubilee law requiring all debt cancellation every fifty years as the legal basis', 'He appealed only to Deuteronomy 15''s sabbatical year release without mentioning the interest prohibition', 'Nehemiah relied on Persian civil law rather than Mosaic law since they were now under Persian jurisdiction', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:7 — "Ye exact usury, every one of his brother." Nehemiah 5:9 — "Ought ye not to walk in the fear of our God because of the reproach of the heathen our enemies?" He combined legal argument (Mosaic law) with theological argument (witness to the nations) to make the strongest possible case.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 3, 'What does Nehemiah 5:10 — "I likewise, and my brethren, and my servants, might exact of them money and corn: I pray you, let us leave off this usury" — reveal about Nehemiah''s rhetorical and ethical strategy?', 'Nehemiah includes himself among the creditors, admits he had a legitimate claim too, and then voluntarily renounces it — removing any accusation of hypocrisy and calling the nobles to match his own example of self-restraint', 'Nehemiah was confessing personal guilt and asking forgiveness before the assembly', 'Nehemiah was establishing that his own loans were larger than the nobles'' and deserved priority repayment', 'The verse shows Nehemiah was unaware of the problem until the people cried out and was admitting negligence', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:10 — "I...might exact...let us leave off." By identifying himself as a creditor who chose to forgo his rights, Nehemiah models what he asks: the argument moves from legal obligation to voluntary covenant generosity, which is far more powerful morally than mere legal compliance.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 4, 'What specific restitution did Nehemiah demand in Nehemiah 5:11, and why is the term "hundredth" (the interest rate) significant?', 'He demanded the immediate return of fields, vineyards, olive yards, and houses plus the hundredth part (1% monthly = approximately 12% annually) of money, corn, wine, and oil that had been charged as interest', 'He demanded all principal be returned with no mention of interest since interest was already paid', '"Hundredth" refers to returning one percent of the total debt as a restoration fee rather than as interest', 'He demanded that the nobles pay a 100-fold penalty for breaking the Mosaic usury law', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:11 — "Restore, I pray you, to them, even this day, their lands, their vineyards, their oliveyards, and their houses, also the hundredth part of the money, and of the corn, the wine, and the oil, that ye exact of them." The "hundredth" (meah) likely refers to the monthly interest rate being charged — 1% per month was standard in the ancient Near East.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 5, 'How does Nehemiah''s account of his governorship in Nehemiah 5:14-18 function within the book as a whole, and what literary purpose does the self-justification serve?', 'It establishes Nehemiah''s moral credibility as the narrator and leader — his sacrifice of the governor''s allowance substantiates his authority to demand sacrifice from the nobles, making his reforms credible rather than self-serving', 'The passage is an official financial accounting required by Persian law for all provincial governors', 'Nehemiah includes the passage to criticise his successors who returned to exploiting the people', 'The self-justification was inserted by a later editor to defend Nehemiah against accusations of personal enrichment', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:14-19 — Nehemiah''s disclosure that he never demanded the governor''s bread allowance and fed 150 people at his own expense (vv.17-18) climaxes with "Yet for all this required not I the bread of the governor, because the bondage was heavy upon this people" (v.18). His sacrifice grounds his moral authority to demand generosity from others.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 6, 'What does the phrase "the fear of God" (yirat Elohim) in Nehemiah 5:9,15 reveal as the theological foundation of Nehemiah''s ethics?', 'The fear of God functions as the ultimate motivator for ethical behaviour — what Mosaic law commands in principle, the fear of God makes operative in practice; Nehemiah appeals to it both as a reason for his own conduct and as the standard he expects from the nobles', 'The phrase is a formulaic religious expression with no specific ethical content in context', 'Nehemiah uses "fear of God" to mean fear of divine punishment rather than reverent relationship', 'The phrase applies only to Nehemiah''s personal piety and is not presented as a standard for the community', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:9 — "Ought ye not to walk in the fear of our God because of the reproach of the heathen our enemies?" and v.15 — "so did not I, because of the fear of God." In both verses, yirat Elohim is the foundation that makes Nehemiah''s conduct righteous and the nobles'' conduct inexcusable.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 7, 'How does the economic justice issue in Nehemiah 5 relate to the prophetic critique of pre-exilic Judah in Isaiah 5:8 and Amos 2:6-7?', 'The nobles'' exploitation mirrors exactly what the pre-exilic prophets condemned — wealthy Israelites seizing the poor''s land and selling fellow Israelites into debt-slavery — showing the exile had not reformed the economic sin patterns that contributed to the original judgment', 'The situation in Nehemiah 5 is entirely different from pre-exilic abuses since it involved Persian taxation rather than native exploitation', 'The prophets condemned only religious apostasy, not economic injustice, making the comparison invalid', 'Nehemiah 5 describes a much milder situation than Isaiah 5 or Amos 2 since no violence was involved', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:5 — "we bring into bondage our sons and daughters to be servants" echoes Amos 2:6 — "they sold the righteous for silver, and the poor for a pair of shoes." Isaiah 5:8 — "Woe unto them that join house to house, that lay field to field" mirrors the land-seizure dynamic of Neh 5:3-4. The post-exilic community was repeating pre-exilic sins.'),
('Nehemiah', 5, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of Nehemiah''s closing prayer "Think upon me, my God, for good, according to all that I have done for this people" (Neh 5:19) as a recurring motif in the book?', 'The prayer recurs at Neh 13:14,22,31 — it is Nehemiah''s consistent appeal to divine accounting as the ultimate validation of his work, substituting God''s judgment for human recognition in a context where earthly reward is uncertain', 'The prayer is a formulaic conclusion to each administrative section and carries no theological weight', 'Nehemiah is boasting before God, which is inconsistent with his otherwise humble character', 'The prayer appears only in chapter 5 and is not a recurring theme in Nehemiah''s memoir', 'a', 'Nehemiah 5:19 — "Think upon me, my God, for good." Same prayer at 13:14 — "Remember me, O my God, concerning this"; 13:22 — "Remember me, O my God, concerning this also"; 13:31 — "Remember me, O my God, for good." The fourfold appeal to divine remembrance structures the entire memoir around accountability to God rather than human approval.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 6 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 6, 'kids', 1, 'How many times did Sanballat and Geshem send messages asking Nehemiah to come and meet them?', 'Four times they sent the same message and Nehemiah answered the same way each time', 'Once Sanballat sent a letter and Nehemiah refused to respond', 'Twice they sent messengers and Nehemiah went into the temple to pray', 'Three times Tobiah wrote and three times Nehemiah ignored the letters', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:4 — "Yet they sent unto me four times after this sort; and I answered them after the same manner."'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'kids', 2, 'What did Nehemiah say when Sanballat tried to scare him into meeting in the valley of Ono?', 'I am doing a great work, so that I cannot come down: why should the work cease?', 'God has sent me to build this wall and no man can stop what God has started', 'I will not come until the wall is finished and the gates are set in place', 'Tell your master that I fear God alone and not the threats of men', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:3 — "I am doing a great work, so that I cannot come down: why should the work cease, whilst I leave it, and come down to you?"'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'kids', 3, 'How many days did it take to finish building the wall of Jerusalem?', 'Fifty-two days', 'Forty days', 'One hundred days', 'Seventy days', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:15 — "So the wall was finished in the twenty and fifth day of the month Elul, in fifty and two days."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 6, 'teens', 1, 'What lie did Sanballat''s fifth letter claim Nehemiah was planning to do?', 'That Nehemiah intended to rebel and make himself king in Judah, and had appointed prophets to preach it', 'That Nehemiah was secretly giving money to the enemies of Persia', 'That Nehemiah had made a treaty with Egypt against King Artaxerxes', 'That Nehemiah planned to murder the nobles and seize the temple treasury', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:6-7 — "It is reported among the heathen, and Gashmu saith it, that thou and the Jews think to rebel: for which cause thou buildest the wall, that thou mayest be their king...And thou hast also appointed prophets to preach of thee at Jerusalem."'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'teens', 2, 'What was Nehemiah''s response to the fifth letter''s false accusation?', 'There are no such things done as thou sayest, but thou feignest them out of thine own heart', 'I will send a report to the king of Persia and let him judge between us', 'These are lies invented by Tobiah and I refuse to answer them', 'God knows my heart and will vindicate me before the king', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:8 — "Then I sent unto him, saying, There are no such things done as thou sayest, but thou feignest them out of thine own heart."'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'teens', 3, 'Who was Shemaiah and what did he falsely prophesy to Nehemiah?', 'He was a false prophet hired by enemies who told Nehemiah to hide in the temple because men were coming to kill him at night', 'He was a Levite who warned Nehemiah that Sanballat was preparing a night attack on the wall', 'He was a legitimate prophet who had a genuine vision of Nehemiah''s death', 'He was Nehemiah''s secretary who misunderstood a dream and reported it as prophecy', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:10-11 — "Shemaiah...said, Let us meet together in the house of God...for they will come to slay thee; yea, in the night will they come to slay thee. And I said, Should such a man as I flee? and who is there, that, being as I am, would go into the temple to save his life?"'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'teens', 4, 'Who had hired Shemaiah and the prophetess Noadiah to frighten Nehemiah?', 'Tobiah and Sanballat had hired him so that Nehemiah would be afraid and sin by entering the temple and be discredited', 'Geshem the Arabian had paid them to distract Nehemiah from completing the gates', 'The Persian governor beyond the river had sent them to delay the wall''s completion', 'The nobles of Judah who feared Nehemiah''s authority had bribed the prophets', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:12-13 — "I perceived that God had not sent him...For Tobiah and Sanballat had hired him. Therefore was he hired, that I should be afraid, and do so, and sin, and that they might have matter for an evil report, that they might reproach me."'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'teens', 5, 'What was the reaction of the surrounding nations when they heard the wall was finished in 52 days?', 'They were much cast down in their own eyes for they perceived that this work was wrought of our God', 'They immediately sent gifts to Jerusalem to honour the builders', 'They planned a new military attack to tear down what had been built', 'They sent a complaint to King Artaxerxes about the speed of the building', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:16 — "And it came to pass, that when all our enemies heard thereof, and all the heathen that were about us saw these things, they were much cast down in their own eyes: for they perceived that this work was wrought of our God."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 1, 'What is the significance of the proposed meeting location "Ono in the plain" (Nehemiah 6:2) and why was Nehemiah right to refuse?', 'Ono was outside Judah on the border of Samaria and Philistia — neutral but isolated territory where Nehemiah would be vulnerable without his full support base, making it an ideal location for an ambush or kidnapping', 'Ono was a sacred site where treaties were formally ratified and Nehemiah had a religious objection to such negotiations', 'The plain of Ono was too far from Jerusalem for Nehemiah to travel and still supervise construction', 'Ono was Sanballat''s home territory and Persian protocol prohibited governors from meeting on a rival''s ground', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:2 — "Come, let us meet together in some one of the villages in the plain of Ono." Nehemiah 6:2b — "But they thought to do me mischief." Ono (modern Khirbet Kefr Ana) is approximately 25 miles northwest of Jerusalem, well outside Judah — far enough to isolate Nehemiah from his supporters.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 2, 'How does Nehemiah''s declaration "I am doing a great work" (Neh 6:3) function both as a practical refusal and as a theological statement about the nature of his task?', 'The phrase "great work" (melacha gedolah) frames the wall-building as divinely commissioned labour — refusing to leave it is not merely prudence but faithfulness to God''s calling, making the distraction an attack on God''s work not just Nehemiah''s schedule', 'The statement is purely a practical excuse to avoid a meeting he had no legitimate reason to refuse', '"Great work" is a standard Persian administrative term for provincial infrastructure projects and carries no theological meaning', 'Nehemiah is being proud and self-important, which the narrator includes as a character flaw', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:3 — "I am doing a great work, so that I cannot come down: why should the work cease, whilst I leave it, and come down to you?" The logic is: the work is God''s work; leaving it for a negotiation would be abandoning God''s commission. The same word (melacha) was used for the tabernacle construction in Exodus 36.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 3, 'What is the political danger embedded in Sanballat''s fifth letter (Neh 6:6-7), and why was the accusation of kingship-aspiration particularly threatening?', 'Under Persian law, claiming or being rumoured to seek kingship in a subject province was treason punishable by death — Sanballat''s letter was designed not merely to frighten Nehemiah but to potentially trigger a Persian investigation that could end the project', 'The accusation was only socially embarrassing and carried no legal consequences under Persian provincial law', 'The letter was a private communication between allies and posed no real danger since Artaxerxes already trusted Nehemiah', 'The danger was religious — being declared a false king would have meant exclusion from the temple community', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:6-7 — "thou...mayest be their king, according to these words...and thou hast also appointed prophets to preach of thee at Jerusalem." If reported to Artaxerxes, this would have made Nehemiah liable to execution. The letter''s power was its potential as a denunciation to the Persian crown.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 4, 'How does Nehemiah discern that Shemaiah''s prophecy was false in Nehemiah 6:10-13, and what criteria did he use?', 'Nehemiah recognised the prophecy was against Torah (a layman entering the inner temple was forbidden, Numbers 18:7) and inconsistent with God''s character — a cowardly flight would contradict his God-given calling, not fulfil it', 'Nehemiah simply distrusted Shemaiah because he was known to be an enemy sympathiser', 'He tested the prophecy by waiting three days to see if additional confirmation came from other prophets', 'Nehemiah consulted Ezra the scribe who confirmed the prophecy was theologically invalid', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:11-12 — "Should such a man as I flee? and who is there, that...would go into the temple to save his life? I will not go in. And, lo, I perceived that God had not sent him." The temple inner area was restricted to priests (Num 18:7); entering it would have been a sin. Nehemiah''s discernment combined Torah knowledge with spiritual insight.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 5, 'What does the network of communication between Tobiah and the nobles of Judah described in Nehemiah 6:17-19 reveal about the internal opposition Nehemiah faced?', 'It reveals that Tobiah had cultivated a fifth column within Jerusalem''s leadership through marriage alliances — he was son-in-law to Shechaniah and his son married the daughter of Meshullam — creating a pro-Tobiah faction inside the community', 'The letters were routine business correspondence with no hostile intent toward Nehemiah', 'The nobles were passing on official Persian communications through Tobiah as a Transjordan official', 'Tobiah''s connections in Jerusalem were purely religious through the priestly network', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:17-19 — "The nobles of Judah sent many letters unto Tobiah, and the letters of Tobiah came unto them...for there were many in Judah sworn unto him, because he was the son in law of Shechaniah...and his son Johanan had taken the daughter of Meshullam." The marriage alliances created a pro-Tobiah lobby within Nehemiah''s own leadership circle.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 6, 'What is the theological significance of Nehemiah''s prayer "Now therefore, O God, strengthen my hands" (Neh 6:9) at the height of the intimidation campaign?', 'Rather than matching slander with slander or seeking political allies, Nehemiah turns immediately to God for strength — modelling that the source of courage in ministry is divine rather than strategic, and prayer is the first not last resort', 'The prayer is a brief interjection with no structural significance in the chapter', 'Nehemiah prays because he has exhausted all practical options and prayer is his fallback position', 'The prayer reveals Nehemiah was on the verge of abandoning the project and needed supernatural intervention', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:9 — "For they all made us afraid, saying, Their hands shall be weakened from the work, that it be not done. Now therefore, O God, strengthen my hands." The structure is: enemy intent (weaken hands) → Nehemiah''s counter (pray for strengthened hands) — the prayer directly reverses the enemy''s stated objective.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 7, 'How does the completion of the wall in 52 days (Nehemiah 6:15) function theologically in the narrative, and what does the enemies'' response reveal?', 'The speed of 52 days — impossibly fast for a city wall — is presented as miraculous divine endorsement; the enemies'' perception that "this work was wrought of our God" (v.16) confirms that even adversaries recognised the supernatural character of the achievement', 'The 52 days was the result of Persian engineering expertise that Nehemiah had imported from Susa', 'The enemies'' response was purely political — they feared Persian retaliation if Artaxerxes'' project was criticised', 'The short timeline means only a portion of the wall was rebuilt and the account is exaggerated', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:15-16 — "the wall was finished in...fifty and two days...they were much cast down in their own eyes: for they perceived that this work was wrought of our God." The mockers of Nehemiah 4:2-3 who said "if a fox go up, he shall break down their stone wall" are silenced by the same wall''s miraculous completion.'),
('Nehemiah', 6, 'adults', 8, 'How does chapter 6''s account of multiple attack vectors — meetings, letters, prophecy, internal networks — illustrate a sophisticated multi-front opposition strategy, and what principle of spiritual leadership does Nehemiah''s consistent response model?', 'Each attack targets a different vulnerability (physical safety, reputation, religious authority, internal loyalty) and Nehemiah''s consistent response — refuse the distraction, reject the fear, return to the work — models a singularity of focus on God''s calling as the defence against multi-vector opposition', 'The opposition was haphazard and uncoordinated; the various attacks were independent acts with no common strategy', 'Nehemiah used different defensive strategies for each attack type, showing adaptable rather than consistent leadership', 'The chapter teaches that political negotiations are always dangerous and should be avoided in ministry contexts', 'a', 'Nehemiah 6:3 (refuse meeting), 6:8 (reject slander), 6:11 (refuse false prophecy), 6:14 (pray against internal prophets). In each case the answer is the same in principle: return to the work and pray. The pattern reveals that Nehemiah''s strength was not tactical versatility but theological clarity about his commission.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 7 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 7, 'kids', 1, 'Who did Nehemiah put in charge of Jerusalem after the wall was finished?', 'Hanani his brother and Hananiah the ruler of the palace', 'Ezra the scribe and the Levites together', 'Tobiah the servant and the elders of Jerusalem', 'The high priest Eliashib and twelve gate captains', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:2 — "I gave my brother Hanani, and Hananiah the ruler of the palace, charge over Jerusalem."'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'kids', 2, 'What did Nehemiah tell the gatekeepers about when to open the gates?', 'Not to open the gates of Jerusalem until the sun was hot, and while the guards were still on watch', 'To open the gates at sunrise and close them at midnight every day', 'To keep the gates open only during the hours of temple sacrifice', 'To open the gates only when Nehemiah himself gave permission each morning', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:3 — "That the gates of Jerusalem shall not be opened until the sun be hot; and while they stand by, let them shut the doors, and bar them: and appoint watches of the inhabitants of Jerusalem, every one in his watch."'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'kids', 3, 'What did God put in Nehemiah''s heart to do when he saw that the city was large but had few people in it?', 'To gather the nobles, rulers, and people to be enrolled in a register according to their families', 'To pray and fast for seven days for God to send more families back to Jerusalem', 'To write to the king of Persia asking him to send more colonists to the city', 'To divide the empty land among the builders who had worked on the wall', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:5 — "My God put into mine heart to gather the nobles, and the rulers, and the people, that they might be reckoned by genealogy."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 7, 'teens', 1, 'What quality did Nehemiah look for in appointing Hananiah as co-ruler of Jerusalem?', 'He was a faithful man and feared God above many', 'He had served as a soldier and proven himself in battle', 'He was well-known to the king of Persia as a trustworthy official', 'He was the eldest son of the high priest and had hereditary authority', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:2 — "For he was a faithful man, and feared God above many."'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'teens', 2, 'What did Nehemiah observe about the physical and demographic state of Jerusalem that prompted his census?', 'The city was large and great but the people were few therein and no houses had been built', 'Many people had moved in but there were not enough priests to serve in the temple', 'The population was large but too concentrated in one part of the city near the water gate', 'The city had many houses but few families had registered with the Persian authorities', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:4 — "Now the city was large and great: but the people were few therein, and the houses were not builded."'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'teens', 3, 'What document did Nehemiah find and use as the basis for the genealogical register in chapter 7?', 'A register of them which came up at the first, which he found written there', 'The temple records kept by Ezra since the first return under Zerubbabel', 'A scroll of names deposited in the king of Persia''s treasury at Susa', 'The priestly genealogy preserved in the tabernacle archives', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:5 — "I found a register of the genealogy of them which came up at the first, and found written therein."'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'teens', 4, 'What happened to the children of the priests who searched for their genealogy but could not find it?', 'They were excluded from the priesthood as polluted until there was a priest who could consult the Urim and Thummim', 'They were assigned to serve as Levites since they could not prove priestly descent', 'They were permitted to continue as priests provisionally until the matter was resolved by the elders', 'They were sent back to Babylon to search the royal archives for their family records', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:64-65 — "These sought their register among those that were reckoned by genealogy, but it was not found: therefore were they, as polluted, put from the priesthood. And the Tirshatha said unto them, that they should not eat of the most holy things, till there stood up a priest with Urim and Thummim."'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'teens', 5, 'What total number of the whole congregation is given at the end of the register in Nehemiah 7?', 'Forty and two thousand three hundred and threescore', 'Fifty thousand five hundred and twenty', 'Thirty thousand and seven hundred', 'Sixty-two thousand and forty', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:66 — "The whole congregation together was forty and two thousand three hundred and threescore."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 1, 'How does the opening of Nehemiah 7 — appointment of gatekeepers, singers, Levites, and security instructions — signal a transition in the book''s theme from construction to community organisation?', 'The wall''s completion shifts the crisis from building to governance; Nehemiah''s first acts after completion are the appointment of trustworthy leadership and strict security protocols, signalling that a rebuilt city without a governed community is incomplete', 'Chapter 7 continues the building narrative with administrative details that are secondary to the construction account', 'The transition is purely chronological and has no thematic significance in the book''s structure', 'The appointments in chapter 7 reverse the building assignments of chapter 3, replacing builders with permanent officials', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:1-3 — "when the wall was built...I appointed...porters and the singers and the Levites...and appointed watches." The sequence — wall completed (6:15), gates set (7:1), officials appointed (7:2), security established (7:3) — shows that the physical wall was only the foundation for the harder work of community rebuilding.'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 2, 'What is the relationship between Nehemiah 7:6-73 and Ezra 2:1-70, and what does the close parallel tell us about the Ezra-Nehemiah literary relationship?', 'The two lists are nearly identical, with minor variations in names and numbers — the parallel demonstrates that Nehemiah 7 deliberately reproduces the first-return register to establish continuity between the original Zerubbabel community and the restored Jerusalem of Nehemiah''s era', 'The lists are completely independent documents that happen to share some names by coincidence', 'Nehemiah 7 is an earlier document that Ezra 2 copied and updated with additional names', 'The parallel shows that the same scribe wrote both books but made errors in copying the numbers between the two versions', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:7 lists the same leaders as Ezra 2:2 (Zerubbabel, Jeshua, Nehemiah, Azariah, Raamiah, Nahamani, Mordecai, Bilshan, Mispereth, Bigvai, Nehum, Baanah). Numbers differ in places (e.g., Neh 7:68 omits horses/mules/camels that appear in Ezra 2:66-67). The parallel is intentional — Nehemiah legitimises the restored community by grounding it in the original return.'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological significance of the criterion Nehemiah uses to select Hananiah — "faithful...feared God above many" (Neh 7:2) — rather than social status or administrative experience?', 'It establishes that in the post-exilic theocracy, covenant faithfulness and fear of God are the foundational qualifications for civic leadership — a counter-cultural standard in a world where office was typically allocated by birth, wealth, or political connection', 'The criteria were simply pragmatic — Nehemiah chose someone he personally trusted without theological calculation', 'Fear of God was a standard Persian administrative qualification for provincial officials', 'The criteria applied only to religious offices; Hananiah''s military role required different qualifications', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:2 — "because he was a faithful man, and feared God above many." Compare the leadership criteria in Exodus 18:21 (Moses'' father-in-law Jethro): "able men, such as fear God, men of truth, hating covetousness." Nehemiah is applying the Mosaic leadership model to the restoration context.'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 4, 'What does the instruction "the gates of Jerusalem shall not be opened until the sun be hot" (Neh 7:3) reveal about the security challenges of the restored city?', 'The delayed opening — unusual compared to normal city practice — prevented enemies from entering during the confusion of early morning when guards were changing and vigilance was lowest; it reflects Nehemiah''s continued awareness of threat even after the wall''s completion', 'The instruction was a religious requirement to allow morning prayers to be completed before commerce began', 'The delay was necessary because the new gates were too heavy to open safely in cold early-morning temperatures', 'The instruction reflects Persian provincial regulations about market opening hours', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:3 — "the gates of Jerusalem shall not be opened until the sun be hot." Ancient Near Eastern cities normally opened gates at dawn for market activity. The deviation signals ongoing security concern — consistent with Sanballat''s unresolved opposition (his letters in chapter 6 showed no resolution of hostility).'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 5, 'How does the phrase "God put into mine heart" (Neh 7:5) function in the narrative as a theological attribution, and how does it compare to similar phrases in the book?', 'It is one of several instances where Nehemiah attributes his initiatives directly to divine prompting rather than personal calculation — a consistent pattern (cf. 2:12 "what my God had put in my heart") that frames the entire restoration as God''s initiative working through a human instrument', 'The phrase is a conventional polite expression in Hebrew narrative meaning simply "I decided"', 'God''s prompting in 7:5 is unique and different from Nehemiah''s own plans described elsewhere in the book', 'The phrase indicates Nehemiah received a prophetic vision rather than an internal sense of direction', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:5 — "my God put into mine heart" echoes 2:12 — "what my God had put in my heart to do at Jerusalem." The repeated attribution shapes the entire narrative: Nehemiah consistently presents himself not as the originator of the restoration but as the responsive instrument of God''s plan.'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 6, 'What does the exclusion of certain priestly families "as polluted" until a priest with Urim and Thummim could verify their genealogy (Neh 7:64-65) reveal about post-exilic concerns regarding priestly purity?', 'It demonstrates that genealogical integrity was considered essential to priestly legitimacy — the disruption of exile had scrambled family records and the post-exilic community treated unverifiable priestly lineage as disqualifying, since priestly service required provable descent from Aaron', 'The exclusion was temporary administrative caution with no theological implication about priestly legitimacy', 'The Urim and Thummim reference shows these instruments were still in common use in the Second Temple period', 'The excluded families were suspected of Gentile intermarriage rather than simply having lost their records', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:64-65 — "polluted, put from the priesthood...till there stood up a priest with Urim and Thummim." The reference to Urim and Thummim is striking since no Second Temple source records their actual use — the text anticipates a future divine adjudication while maintaining strict present standards, reflecting the seriousness with which priestly lineage was guarded.'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 7, 'How does the demographic observation of Nehemiah 7:4 — "the city was large and great: but the people were few therein" — set up the resettlement narrative of Nehemiah 11?', 'Chapter 7''s census and its revelation of under-population is the problem that chapter 11''s forced and voluntary resettlement of Jerusalem solves — the census data provides the foundation for the community decision to populate the holy city', 'Chapter 7 and chapter 11 are independent sections with no intended narrative connection', 'The observation in chapter 7 leads directly to Nehemiah building new houses in chapter 8', 'The depopulation issue was resolved naturally over the following months without any organised resettlement', 'a', 'Nehemiah 7:4 — "people were few...and the houses were not builded" is answered by Nehemiah 11:1-2 — "the rulers of the people dwelt at Jerusalem: the rest of the people also cast lots, to bring one of ten to dwell in Jerusalem...And the people blessed all the men, that willingly offered themselves to dwell at Jerusalem." Chapter 7 identifies the problem; chapter 11 records its resolution.'),
('Nehemiah', 7, 'adults', 8, 'What is the literary function of the genealogical register in Nehemiah 7 within the overall structure of the book, and how does it contribute to the theological theme of continuity?', 'The register anchors the restored community in the first return under Zerubbabel, establishing that Nehemiah''s rebuilt Jerusalem is not a new creation but the continuation of God''s covenant people — the same families who returned under Cyrus are now inhabiting a secured city', 'The register is a historical appendix with no literary or theological function in the book''s structure', 'The list was included simply to provide detailed census data for the Persian provincial records', 'The register''s function is to identify who had the legal right to the land, not to establish theological continuity', 'a', 'The register of Neh 7 (= Ezra 2) placed here between the wall''s completion (ch.6) and the covenant renewal (chs.8-10) forms a bridge: the community that hears the Law and signs the covenant in chapters 8-10 is identified as the same genealogical community that came out of Babylon — God''s promise of restoration has been fulfilled for these specific people.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 8 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 8, 'kids', 1, 'Who read the book of the Law of Moses to all the people gathered at the Water Gate?', 'Ezra the scribe', 'Nehemiah the governor', 'The high priest Eliashib', 'The Levites standing on a wooden platform', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:1-2 — "All the people gathered themselves together...and they spake unto Ezra the scribe to bring the book of the law of Moses...And Ezra the priest brought the law."'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'kids', 2, 'What did all the people do when Ezra opened the book of the Law?', 'They stood up and said Amen, Amen, and bowed their heads and worshipped with their faces to the ground', 'They began to weep and tear their clothes in sorrow', 'They sang a psalm of praise together with loud voices', 'They sat in silence for a whole hour while Ezra read', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:5-6 — "When he opened it, all the people stood up: And Ezra blessed the LORD...and all the people answered, Amen, Amen...and they bowed their heads, and worshipped the LORD with their faces to the ground."'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'kids', 3, 'What feast did the people celebrate after hearing the Law read, living in leafy booths for seven days?', 'The Feast of Tabernacles, also called the Feast of Booths', 'The Passover feast with unleavened bread', 'The Feast of Weeks with firstfruits offerings', 'The Day of Atonement with fasting and prayer', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:14-17 — "they found written in the law...that the children of Israel should dwell in booths in the feast of the seventh month...And all the congregation of them that were come again out of the captivity made booths, and sat under the booths."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 8, 'teens', 1, 'From what time of day to what time did Ezra read the Law to the assembled people?', 'From the morning until midday, from early morning until noon', 'From sunrise to sunset without stopping', 'From the third hour to the ninth hour of the day', 'From dawn until the evening sacrifice', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:3 — "He read therein before the street that was before the water gate from the morning until midday, before the men and the women, and those that could understand; and the ears of all the people were attentive unto the book of the law."'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'teens', 2, 'What did the Levites do for the people as Ezra read the Law so they could understand it?', 'They gave the sense and caused the people to understand the reading', 'They translated the Law from Hebrew into Aramaic for the people', 'They wrote down the key passages on clay tablets for the people to keep', 'They explained which parts of the Law were still in force and which were fulfilled', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:8 — "So they read in the book in the law of God distinctly, and gave the sense, and caused them to understand the reading."'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'teens', 3, 'What did Nehemiah, Ezra, and the Levites tell the weeping people on the holy day?', 'This day is holy unto the LORD your God; mourn not, nor weep — the joy of the LORD is your strength', 'Go and fast and pray for God has forgiven your sins on this holy day', 'Be silent for the reading of the Law requires reverence not weeping', 'Put on sackcloth for you have greatly sinned against God''s law', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:9-10 — "This day is holy unto the LORD your God; mourn not, nor weep...Go your way, eat the fat, and drink the sweet...for this day is holy unto our Lord: neither be ye sorry; for the joy of the LORD is your strength."'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'teens', 4, 'What did Nehemiah tell the people to send to those who had nothing prepared for the feast day?', 'Portions to those for whom nothing is prepared, because the day is holy', 'Firstfruits from their fields to the temple for the priests and Levites', 'Tithes of their increase to the Levites who had taught them the Law', 'Offerings of silver and gold to be stored in the temple treasury', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:10 — "send portions unto them for whom nothing is prepared: for this day is holy unto our Lord."'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'teens', 5, 'What did the text say had not been done since the days of Joshua when the people celebrated the Feast of Tabernacles?', 'From the days of Jeshua the son of Nun unto that day had not the children of Israel done so — such great gladness', 'The Feast of Tabernacles had not been kept with booths in Jerusalem since Solomon''s time', 'No reading of the Law during the feast had occurred since the time of Samuel', 'The building of booths on the rooftops and courts had not been practised since the first wilderness wandering', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:17 — "And all the congregation of them that were come again out of the captivity made booths, and sat under the booths: for since the days of Jeshua the son of Nun unto that day had not the children of Israel done so. And there was very great gladness."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 1, 'What is the significance of the people''s spontaneous request for the Law in Nehemiah 8:1 — "they spake unto Ezra the scribe to bring the book of the law of Moses" — rather than Ezra imposing it on them?', 'The reading was initiated by popular demand, not prophetic decree or governor''s order — the community itself requested the Law, making the covenant renewal of chapters 9-10 an authentic grass-roots response rather than a top-down imposition', 'The people asked because they were legally required to hear the Law read at the Feast of Tabernacles', 'Nehemiah had instructed the elders to ask Ezra to read the Law as a prepared part of the dedication ceremony', 'The request was from the priests and Levites rather than from the common people', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:1 — "all the people gathered themselves together as one man...and they spake unto Ezra the scribe to bring the book of the law of Moses." The collective initiative ("as one man") from the whole people makes this a covenantal assembly from the bottom up.'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 2, 'What does the phrase "gave the sense" (Neh 8:8) indicate about the linguistic situation of the returnees and the hermeneutical task of the Levites?', 'The phrase indicates that the Levites provided translation or explanatory paraphrase — likely from Hebrew into Aramaic (the lingua franca of the exiles) — and interpreted the meaning, representing the earliest recorded instance of synagogue-style expository teaching', 'The Levites simply read more slowly and clearly since the text was difficult to hear at the large gathering', '"Gave the sense" refers to giving the emotional and spiritual sense of the text through chanting and music', 'The Levites were filling in gaps in the text that were damaged or unclear in the scroll', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:8 — "So they read in the book in the law of God distinctly, and gave the sense, and caused them to understand the reading." Many scholars interpret this as Targum-style Aramaic translation plus explanation, since Jewish exiles in Babylon would have lost fluency in biblical Hebrew — a key moment in the development of the synagogue and biblical interpretation tradition.'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 3, 'How does the theological principle "the joy of the LORD is your strength" (Neh 8:10) function within its immediate narrative context of weeping over the Law?', 'The command shifts the people''s orientation from guilt about past failures (appropriate but not the final word) to joy in God''s grace and presence — demonstrating that hearing God''s word rightly leads not to paralysis but to energised celebration of God''s goodness', 'The verse is a statement of general principle unrelated to the specific context of Law-reading and grief', 'Nehemiah was correcting unhealthy emotionalism and telling people to maintain rational composure', 'The joy referenced is the external festival celebration rather than inward spiritual disposition', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:9-10 — The people wept when they heard the Law (v.9 — appropriate response to conviction); Nehemiah and Ezra redirect them to joy (v.10 — appropriate response to grace). The sequence models the gospel structure: hearing the Law produces conviction; God''s grace provides joy that becomes the source of strength for obedience.'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 4, 'What is the structural relationship between Nehemiah 8 (Law-reading), chapter 9 (confession), and chapter 10 (covenant signing), and how does this sequence reflect biblical covenant-renewal theology?', 'The sequence follows the classic covenant pattern: Word proclaimed (ch.8) → conviction and confession (ch.9) → commitment and covenant (ch.10) — mirroring Deuteronomy''s structure of Torah proclamation, Israel''s history recounted, and covenant renewal', 'The three chapters are independent events with no intended structural connection', 'Chapter 9''s confession precedes the Law-reading of chapter 8 in the actual chronology', 'The covenant-renewal is purely legal and the spiritual response of chapters 8-9 is incidental rather than structurally significant', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:1-18 (Word read and understood), 9:1-38 (history recounted, sin confessed), 10:1-39 (covenant signed with specific obligations) form a unified covenant renewal ceremony. Compare Deuteronomy: Moses proclaims Torah (Deut 1-26), Israel''s history rehearsed (Deut 1-3), covenant renewed with specific stipulations (Deut 27-28).'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 5, 'What does the detail that the reading platform had six men on Ezra''s right and six on his left (Neh 8:4) reveal about the public nature and official character of the assembly?', 'The thirteen named officials flanking Ezra (twelve named + Ezra) represent a formal, witnessed, publicly authorised reading of the Law — not a private instruction but a constitutional act before the whole community with communal leaders as official witnesses', 'The arrangement was purely practical — the platform was large enough to accommodate Ezra and his assistants for organisational purposes', 'The six-plus-six arrangement was a ceremonial pattern from Mosaic protocol for Law-readings at the tent of meeting', 'The officials flanking Ezra were the priests and Levites who would do the explaining after each section', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:4 — "Ezra the scribe stood upon a pulpit of wood...and beside him stood Mattithiah, and Shema, and Anaiah, and Urijah, and Hilkiah, and Maaseiah, on his right hand; and on his left hand, Pedaiah, and Mishael, and Malchiah, and Hashum, and Hashbadana, Zechariah, and Meshullam." The named witnesses authenticate this as a solemn public constitutional moment.'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 6, 'Why is the Feast of Tabernacles'' celebration in Nehemiah 8 described as unprecedented since the time of Joshua (Neh 8:17), given that 2 Chronicles 7:8-10 records Solomon''s great feast?', 'The qualification is likely specific to the booth-dwelling aspect and the intensity of gladness — either the exile had broken the tradition of actual physical booth construction or the combination of all its elements had not been observed in its full form for centuries', 'The author of Nehemiah was unaware of Solomon''s feast and made an error', 'The verse means only that this feast was the largest in terms of participants rather than that no feast had been held before', '2 Chronicles 7 describes a different feast — the temple dedication — not the Feast of Tabernacles, so there is no contradiction', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:17 — "since the days of Jeshua the son of Nun unto that day had not the children of Israel done so." Compare 2 Chronicles 7:8-10 (Solomon''s feast, seventh month, booths). Ezra 3:4 records a Feast of Tabernacles under Zerubbabel. The hyperbole likely emphasises the quality of joy, the completeness of observance, and the covenant-renewal context rather than making a strictly historical claim.'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 7, 'What does the instruction to build booths "upon the roofs of their houses, and in their courts, and in the courts of the house of God, and in the street of the water gate, and in the street of the gate of Ephraim" (Neh 8:16) reveal about the geography and scale of the festival?', 'The multiple booth locations show the feast involved the entire city — private homes, public streets, and the temple precinct — making it a total-environment celebration that transformed all of Jerusalem into a symbolic wilderness camp before God', 'The different locations indicate different social classes were separated for the festival observance', 'The multiple sites were practical necessity because no single location was large enough to hold the entire population', 'The locations were assigned by priestly regulations governing which groups could celebrate in which areas', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:16 — The distribution of booth locations across rooftops, courts, temple area, and public streets shows the feast spilled out of any single venue into the whole inhabited city. Leviticus 23:42 requires all Israel to dwell in booths — the geography of Nehemiah 8:16 shows this was taken literally and comprehensively.'),
('Nehemiah', 8, 'adults', 8, 'How does the figure of Ezra the scribe and priest standing on the wooden platform in Nehemiah 8 function as a model for the ministry of the Word, and what does it prefigure in later Jewish and Christian practice?', 'Ezra''s public reading from an elevated pulpit, with Levitical explanatory teaching, communal response (Amen, prostration), and application to festival observance represents the prototype of synagogue worship and later Christian Word-ministry including expository preaching, congregational response, and doxological framing', 'The scene is unique to the post-exilic crisis and has no lasting institutional significance', 'Ezra''s role prefigures only the role of the high priest, not the later synagogue reader or preacher', 'The wooden pulpit was a one-time emergency platform and the model was not carried forward into regular Jewish practice', 'a', 'Nehemiah 8:4-8 — elevated pulpit, public reading, Levitical explanation, congregational standing and response. This scene is widely regarded as the institutional foundation of synagogue worship: the bimah (reading platform), Torah portion reading, targum/explanation, congregational Amen. Luke 4:16-21 shows Jesus standing in the synagogue to read — the same pattern — and the Christian sermon inherits this tradition.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 9 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 9, 'kids', 1, 'What did the Israelites do on the twenty-fourth day of the month after the Feast of Tabernacles?', 'They gathered with fasting, sackcloth, and earth upon them to confess their sins', 'They celebrated a second feast of thanksgiving with music and singing', 'They went back to work rebuilding the houses inside Jerusalem', 'They offered burnt offerings at the temple for seven days', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:1 — "Now in the twenty and fourth day of this month the children of Israel were assembled with fasting, and with sackclothes, and earth upon them."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'kids', 2, 'What did the Israelites do with the seed of Israel before making their confession?', 'They separated themselves from all strangers and stood and confessed their sins', 'They gathered the children together and taught them the law of Moses', 'They sent away all the foreign workers from the wall project', 'They divided the people by tribe to make an orderly procession', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:2 — "And the seed of Israel separated themselves from all strangers, and stood and confessed their sins, and the iniquities of their fathers."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'kids', 3, 'How long did the people stand and read the Law and how long did they confess and worship?', 'One fourth part of the day reading the Law and one fourth part confessing and worshipping', 'They fasted all day and then prayed through the night', 'They read for one hour and prayed for three hours', 'They spent the morning in the temple and the afternoon in the streets', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:3 — "They stood up in their place, and read in the book of the law of the LORD their God one fourth part of the day; and another fourth part they confessed, and worshipped the LORD their God."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 9, 'teens', 1, 'What did the Levites call the people to do at the beginning of the prayer in Nehemiah 9:5?', 'Stand up and bless the LORD your God for ever and ever — blessed be thy glorious name, which is exalted above all blessing and praise', 'Bow down before the LORD and present your offerings of repentance', 'Lift up your hands and confess your iniquities before the whole assembly', 'Sing a new song to the LORD who is worthy of all honour and glory', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:5 — "Then the Levites...said, Stand up and bless the LORD your God for ever and ever: and blessed be thy glorious name, which is exalted above all blessing and praise."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'teens', 2, 'What event from creation does the long prayer in Nehemiah 9 begin with?', 'Thou, even thou, art LORD alone; thou hast made heaven, the heaven of heavens, with all their host, the earth and all things therein', 'In the beginning God created man in his own image and breathed life into him', 'Thou didst call Abraham out of Ur and make a covenant with him about the land', 'Thou madest the sea and divided the waters above from the waters below', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:6 — "Thou, even thou, art LORD alone; thou hast made heaven, the heaven of heavens, with all their host, the earth, and all things that are therein, the seas, and all that is therein."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'teens', 3, 'What did the prayer say God did at the Red Sea when the Egyptians pursued Israel?', 'Thou heardest their cry by the Red sea and shewedst signs and wonders upon Pharaoh and dividedst the sea before them', 'God sent a great wind and dried up the sea for a path to pass through', 'The LORD drowned the Egyptians in the sea before Israel had even reached the shore', 'God appeared in fire and drove back the army of Egypt before Israel crossed', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:9,11 — "And didst see the affliction of our fathers in Egypt, and heardest their cry by the Red sea...And thou didst divide the sea before them, so that they went through the midst of the sea on the dry land; and their persecutors thou threwest into the deeps."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'teens', 4, 'What did the prayer say Israel did even after God had given them his good Spirit and brought them bread from heaven and water from the rock?', 'They were disobedient and rebelled against God and cast his law behind their backs and slew his prophets', 'They forgot God for forty years and worshipped the gods of Canaan', 'They returned to Egypt and asked Pharaoh to be their ruler again', 'They refused to enter the promised land and wandered for a generation', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:26 — "Nevertheless they were disobedient, and rebelled against thee, and cast thy law behind their backs, and slew thy prophets which testified against them to turn them to thee."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'teens', 5, 'How did the prayer describe God''s character in the repeated cycle of Israel''s sin and God''s rescue?', 'God was a God of great mercies who did not forsake them, and gave them saviours who saved them out of the hand of their enemies', 'God punished Israel and then turned his face away until they cried to him again', 'The LORD delivered Israel only when the whole nation repented with fasting and prayer', 'God sent angels to rescue them each time but never personally intervened in their history', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:27 — "Therefore thou deliveredst them into the hand of their enemies...but after they had rest, they did evil again before thee...and many times didst thou deliver them according to thy mercies; And gavest them saviours, who saved them out of the hand of their enemies."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 1, 'What is the literary genre of Nehemiah 9:6-37 and how does it function within the book''s covenant-renewal narrative?', 'It is a recital prayer (or covenant lawsuit) — a sustained historical retrospective from creation to the current crisis, functioning as the theological basis for the covenant commitment of chapter 10 by demonstrating both God''s faithfulness and Israel''s chronic unfaithfulness', 'It is a royal psalm of praise borrowed from the Psalter and inserted by Ezra for liturgical purposes', 'The prayer is a personal lament by Nehemiah that was later generalised to include the whole community', 'It functions as a historical document rather than a prayer, recording events for Persian administrative records', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:6-37 moves from creation (v.6) through Abraham (vv.7-8), Exodus (vv.9-11), Sinai (vv.13-14), wilderness (vv.15-21), conquest (vv.22-25), judges (vv.26-28), prophets (vv.29-31) to present distress (vv.32-37). This form parallels Psalms 78, 105, 106 and Deuteronomy 1-3 — a covenant renewal prayer grounded in historical recital.'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 2, 'How does the prayer''s treatment of the Abraham covenant in Nehemiah 9:7-8 function as the theological foundation for the entire historical recital?', 'By beginning with God''s unconditional choice of Abraham and his faithfulness to the covenant promise, the prayer establishes that Israel''s continued existence and restoration is rooted in God''s own righteousness rather than Israel''s merit — making repentance possible rather than hopeless', 'The Abraham reference is purely historical and establishes only the land claim, not the theological basis for forgiveness', 'The prayer begins with Abraham to contrast his faithfulness with Israel''s unfaithfulness in the wilderness', 'The Abraham section is a later interpolation that interrupts the original prayer which moved directly from creation to Exodus', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:7-8 — "Thou art the LORD the God, who didst choose Abram...and madest a covenant with him...and hast performed thy words; for thou art righteous." The affirmation of divine righteousness (tzaddik) in the context of covenant faithfulness establishes the basis for the later appeal: God''s own character compels him to remember his covenant.'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 3, 'What is the theological significance of the phrase "thou art a God ready to pardon, gracious and merciful, slow to anger, and of great kindness" (Neh 9:17) in the context of the golden calf narrative it references?', 'The prayer quotes almost verbatim the divine self-revelation to Moses in Exodus 34:6-7 after the golden calf — applying the very attributes God proclaimed as the basis for renewed covenant after Israel''s worst sin as the ground for restoration in the post-exilic context', 'The phrase is a general liturgical formula used in all Israelite prayer without specific reference to Exodus 34', 'The prayer contrasts God''s character with the harshness of Babylon to make a political argument for release from Persian servitude', 'The attributes listed here are unique to Nehemiah 9 and do not appear elsewhere in the Old Testament', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:17 — "thou art a God ready to pardon, gracious and merciful, slow to anger, and of great kindness." Compare Exodus 34:6 — "The LORD, The LORD God, merciful and gracious, longsuffering, and abundant in goodness and truth." The prayer deliberately invokes the Sinai covenant renewal formula as the theological basis for the post-exilic renewal.'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 4, 'How does the prayer''s description of the wilderness provision in Nehemiah 9:19-21 — "the pillar of cloud...pillar of fire...good spirit...manna...water" — function rhetorically in the confession?', 'By cataloguing God''s sustained provision for forty years of rebellion, the prayer highlights the disproportion between divine generosity and human ingratitude — making Israel''s sin more culpable while simultaneously demonstrating that God''s mercy exceeds human unfaithfulness', 'The wilderness provision is mentioned to establish Israel''s desert survival skills as preparation for the Canaan conquest', 'The catalogue of provisions is a legal defence of Israel''s behaviour — they were grateful for what God gave them', 'The wilderness section is a separate poem inserted into the prayer that disrupts the logical flow of the confession', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:19-21 — "Thou in thy manifold mercies forsookest them not in the wilderness...Thou gavest also thy good spirit to instruct them, and withheldest not thy manna...and gavest them water for their thirst. Yea, forty years didst thou sustain them in the wilderness, so that they lacked nothing." The comprehensive provision list makes the rebellion of v.26 all the more shocking.'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 5, 'What does the repeated "yet...but thou" pattern in Nehemiah 9:16-17, 26-27, 28-31 reveal about the prayer''s theological structure?', 'The antiphonal pattern — Israel''s sin ("yet/nevertheless they") contrasted with divine mercy ("but thou") — creates a literary rhythm that embodies the entire history of the covenant: every act of human faithlessness is met by a greater act of divine mercy', 'The pattern is a stylistic feature of Hebrew poetry with no theological significance', 'The "yet...but thou" pattern shows that God punished Israel first and then relented only under their pressure', 'The pattern reveals that the prayer was composed by two different authors whose sections were later combined', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:16-17 — "But they...acted presumptuously...but thou art a God ready to pardon." 9:26-27 — "Nevertheless they...rebelled...therefore thou deliveredst them...but after they had rest...thou deliveredst them." 9:28-31 — "But after they had rest...therefore leftest thou them...yet thou...for thou art a gracious and merciful God." The structure is a sustained literary embodiment of Lamentations 3:22 — "It is of the LORD''s mercies that we are not consumed."'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 6, 'How does Nehemiah 9:32-37 function as the hinge between the historical recital and the covenant of chapter 10?', 'It shifts from "thou hast been faithful/we have been unfaithful" to "therefore NOW let not all this trouble seem little before thee" — applying the historical theology to the present crisis and creating the theological urgency for the covenant commitment that follows in chapter 10', 'The passage simply summarises the prayer and has no transitional function between chapters 9 and 10', 'Verses 32-37 are a later addition to the prayer that was composed after the covenant signing of chapter 10', 'The hinge is purely chronological — the prayer ended and the signatories were named the following day', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:32 — "Now therefore, our God, the great, the mighty, and the terrible God, who keepest covenant and mercy, let not all the trouble seem little before thee." The "now therefore" (we''attah) is the pivotal term that turns theological recital into present petition — the same rhetorical move found in Moses'' prayers and Daniel 9:17-19.'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 7, 'What is the significance of the prayer''s closing description of the people as "servants in the land" (Neh 9:36) that God gave to their fathers?', 'It creates a powerful irony: the land promise to Abraham is fulfilled geographically but not experientially — they are in the land but as Persian subjects, not as free covenant people — making the restored walls inadequate without renewed covenant faithfulness', 'The statement is a complaint about Persian taxation with no deeper theological meaning', 'The people are describing themselves as temple servants who minister before God', '"Servants in the land" refers specifically to the working conditions of the wall-builders who had not yet been released from their labour contracts', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:36-37 — "we are servants this day, and for the land that thou gavest unto our fathers...behold, we are servants in it: And it yieldeth much increase unto the kings whom thou hast set over us...also they have dominion over our bodies." The land is producing wealth — but for Persian kings, not for God''s people. This is the unresolved tension that makes the covenant commitment of chapter 10 urgent.'),
('Nehemiah', 9, 'adults', 8, 'How does the prayer of Nehemiah 9 model the practice of lament and intercession for subsequent generations, and what distinguishes it from mere complaint?', 'The prayer transforms historical complaint into covenantal intercession by grounding every present sorrow in God''s proven faithfulness — it does not stop at Israel''s sin or present suffering but consistently returns to divine character as the basis for expectation, avoiding both despair and presumption', 'The prayer is a complaint without resolution and ends in unresolved tension, making it a model of honest lament without petition', 'The prayer''s length and detail make it unsuitable as a personal prayer model — it functions only as communal liturgy', 'Nehemiah 9 differs from lament psalms by focusing only on historical events and making no personal application to the present community', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9 integrates the elements of genuine lament-intercession: historical recital of God''s acts (vv.6-25), honest acknowledgment of sin (vv.16-17,26-30), recognition of justice in punishment (vv.33), appeal to divine character (vv.17,31), present petition (vv.32-37), and covenant commitment (v.38). Compare Psalm 106 which follows the same structure in poetic form.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 10 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 10, 'kids', 1, 'What did the people enter into at the end of chapter 10 — a sure covenant with a curse and an oath?', 'A sure covenant, and wrote it and sealed it with the names of their princes, Levites, and priests', 'A peace agreement with all the surrounding nations', 'A new set of building laws for the city of Jerusalem', 'A treaty with King Artaxerxes to remain loyal to Persia', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:1 — "Now those that sealed were, Nehemiah, the Tirshatha..."; 9:38 — "And because of all this we make a sure covenant, and write it; and our princes, Levites, and priests, seal unto it."'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'kids', 2, 'What did the people promise about keeping the Sabbath day regarding buying and selling?', 'That they would not buy from the heathen on the sabbath or holy day', 'That they would close the temple market every seventh day', 'That all merchants would rest on the sabbath and pay a fine if they worked', 'That they would fast on the sabbath and give the day''s food to the poor', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:31 — "And if the people of the land bring ware or any victuals on the sabbath day to sell, that we would not buy it of them on the sabbath, or on an holy day."'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'kids', 3, 'What did the people promise to bring to the house of God every year?', 'The firstfruits of their ground, and the firstlings of all fruit, and the firstborn of their sons', 'A tenth of all their silver and gold to store in the treasury', 'A yearly offering of wood from every family for the altar fire', 'All their grain and wine and oil to be divided among the priests and Levites', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:35-37 — "And to bring the firstfruits of our ground, and the firstfruits of all fruit of all trees...the firstborn of our sons, and of our cattle...and the firstlings of our herds and of our flocks."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 10, 'teens', 1, 'Who was the first signatory on the sealed covenant in Nehemiah 10:1?', 'Nehemiah, the Tirshatha, the son of Hachaliah', 'Ezra the priest and scribe', 'Eliashib the high priest', 'Zedekiah the prince of Judah', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:1 — "Now those that sealed were, Nehemiah, the Tirshatha, the son of Hachaliah, and Zidkijah."'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'teens', 2, 'What specific commitment did the people make concerning their daughters and foreign women?', 'We would not give our daughters unto the people of the land, nor take their daughters for our sons', 'All foreign wives would be required to learn the Law of Moses within one year', 'Daughters could only marry within their own tribe to preserve the inheritance', 'Foreign women already married would be permitted to stay but no new marriages allowed', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:30 — "That we would not give our daughters unto the people of the land, nor take their daughters for our sons."'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'teens', 3, 'What specific year did the people agree to observe regarding the land and debt?', 'The seventh year — forgiving every debt and letting the land rest', 'The Jubilee year — returning all sold property every fifty years', 'The third year — bringing the full tithe to the storehouse', 'The first year of each new governor — making a fresh tax assessment', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:31 — "And that we would leave the seventh year, and the exaction of every debt."'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'teens', 4, 'What was the wood offering that the people organised and what was it used for?', 'They cast lots among the priests, Levites, and people to bring wood for the altar at set times each year to keep the fire burning continually', 'They agreed to cut timber from the forest annually and sell it to fund the temple repairs', 'Every family agreed to bring a bundle of wood each week to the temple storehouses', 'The wood offering was a one-time contribution to build benches for the temple courts', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:34 — "And we cast the lots among the priests, the Levites, and the people, for the wood offering, to bring it into the house of our God, after the houses of our fathers, at times appointed year by year, to burn upon the altar of the LORD our God."'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'teens', 5, 'What summary statement concluded all the covenant commitments in Nehemiah 10:39?', 'We will not forsake the house of our God', 'We will walk in God''s law and keep all his commandments and statutes forever', 'We will pay all our tithes and restore what was taken from the Levites', 'We will observe the sabbath and teach our children the law of Moses', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:39 — "We will not forsake the house of our God."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 1, 'What is the relationship between the covenant commitments of Nehemiah 10 and the specific failures that Nehemiah addresses in chapter 13?', 'The three main commitments — no intermarriage (10:30), Sabbath commerce (10:31), temple support (10:32-39) — correspond precisely to the three reforms Nehemiah enforces upon his return in chapter 13 (intermarriage 13:23-28, Sabbath 13:15-22, temple provisions 13:10-14), showing that the covenant was violated almost immediately', 'The covenant of chapter 10 was largely kept and chapter 13 addresses minor infractions by a small minority', 'Chapter 13''s reforms address entirely different issues from the covenant commitments, indicating the covenant was about different concerns', 'The connection between chapters 10 and 13 is purely coincidental since they cover topics that were always recurring problems in Judah', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:30 — no intermarriage; 13:23-28 — confronts intermarriage. Neh 10:31 — no Sabbath commerce; 13:15-22 — shuts gates on Sabbath. Neh 10:32-39 — temple support commitments; 13:10-14 — restores Levites abandoned because portions not paid. The symmetry is exact and devastating: the community violated its own signed covenant within Nehemiah''s lifetime.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 2, 'What is the significance of the covenant being sealed (hatham) rather than merely sworn (shava), and what does this distinction imply about its binding character?', 'Sealing a document with a personal seal (as opposed to a verbal oath) created a legal instrument — a written, witnessed, permanently accessible record — making the covenant more formally binding and harder to repudiate than a spoken promise', 'Sealing was a religious ritual with no additional legal force beyond the spoken oath', 'The seal indicates the document was filed with the Persian provincial administration for official recognition', 'Sealing meant the document was to be kept secret and not read publicly — the opposite of a public covenant', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:38 — "we make a sure covenant, and write it; and our princes, Levites, and priests, seal unto it." Nehemiah 10:1 then lists 84 named individuals who sealed. In the ancient Near East, a sealed document (cf. Jeremiah 32:10-14) was a legally binding instrument. The writing and sealing combined oral commitment with permanent documentary record.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 3, 'How does the half-shekel temple tax instituted in Nehemiah 10:32 relate to the Mosaic law of Exodus 30:11-16, and what does the difference reveal?', 'Exodus 30 prescribed a half-shekel census tax paid once when numbered; Nehemiah 10:32 institutes a third of a shekel as an annual temple maintenance tax — showing post-exilic adaptation of Mosaic law to new fiscal realities in a community without full sovereignty', 'The amounts are identical and Nehemiah was simply reapplying Exodus 30 with no modification', 'The difference indicates Nehemiah was ignorant of Exodus 30 and independently created his own tax system', 'Nehemiah''s third-shekel replaced the half-shekel permanently, nullifying the Exodus 30 provision', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:32 — "Also we made ordinances for us, to charge ourselves yearly with the third part of a shekel for the service of the house of our God." Exodus 30:13 — "half a shekel after the shekel of the sanctuary." The reduction to a third shekel may reflect lower economic capacity of the returnees or a devalued shekel standard — either way it shows principled adaptation rather than abrogation of the Mosaic template.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 4, 'What is the theological significance of the wood offering (Neh 10:34) as an innovation not explicitly required by Mosaic law?', 'It demonstrates post-exilic community creativity in fulfilling the spirit of Mosaic law (Leviticus 6:12-13 — the altar fire to burn continually) by organising a practical rota for fuel supply that the Mosaic law assumed but did not specify — showing that covenant faithfulness requires practical application beyond the letter of the text', 'The wood offering was a pagan practice borrowed from Canaanite religion that was later condemned by the prophets', 'The wood offering replaced the burnt offerings since the community could not afford animals', 'The offering is explicitly prescribed in Deuteronomy 29 but was never observed before Nehemiah''s time', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:34 — "for the wood offering, to bring it into the house of our God...to burn upon the altar of the LORD our God, as it is written in the law." Leviticus 6:12-13 requires continuous fire but prescribes no wood rota. Nehemiah 10 fills the practical gap, and Nehemiah 13:31 later includes the wood offering among reforms Nehemiah asks God to remember — confirming its ongoing importance.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 5, 'How does the catalogue of tithes and firstfruits in Nehemiah 10:35-39 reflect the Numbers 18 and Deuteronomy 14 Levitical support system, and what is the theological rationale for these obligations?', 'The commitments in 10:35-39 map systematically onto Numbers 18:8-32 (priestly and Levitical portions) and Deuteronomy 14:22-29 (tithes including the Levite portion) — the theological rationale is that the Levites have no land inheritance, so the entire community''s worship obligation sustains those who serve God on their behalf', 'The tithes in Nehemiah 10 are an innovation since the Mosaic tithes applied only to agricultural surplus and were never intended as regular annual obligations', 'The obligations of chapter 10 contradict Numbers 18 by adding requirements that Mosaic law never imposed', 'The tithes were paid to the Persian treasury rather than to the Levites during this period, making the Nehemiah 10 commitments aspirational rather than current', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:37-38 — "the first fruits of our dough, and our offerings...the tithes of our ground unto the Levites, that the same Levites might have the tithes in all the cities of our tillage...And the priest the son of Aaron shall be with the Levites, when the Levites take tithes." This precisely mirrors Numbers 18:21-28 — the Levites receive tithes from the people and give a tenth of that to the priests.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 6, 'What does the list of 84 signatories in Nehemiah 10:1-27 reveal about the representative structure of the post-exilic community?', 'The list covers three categories: civil leaders (Nehemiah + Zidkijah, v.1), priestly families (22 names, vv.2-8), Levites (17 names, vv.9-13), and lay leaders (44 names, vv.14-27) — showing that the covenant was a representative act binding the whole community through its duly constituted leaders', 'The 84 signatories were the only people committed to the covenant; the rest of the community was exempt', 'The list is purely honorific and the individuals named had no special covenant responsibility beyond other community members', 'The three categories reflect Persian administrative divisions rather than Israelite covenant structures', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:28-29 — "And the rest of the people...every one having knowledge, and having understanding; They clave to their brethren, their nobles, and entered into a curse, and into an oath, to walk in God''s law." The 84 signatories led a representative covenant that the entire community then joined by oath — the leaders signed for all.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 7, 'What is the covenant-treaty form evidenced in Nehemiah 10, and how does it compare to ancient Near Eastern suzerainty treaties?', 'The covenant follows the vassal-treaty pattern: historical preamble (ch.9), stipulations (ch.10:30-39), and implicit sanctions (the curse of v.29) — adapting the suzerainty format to a covenant where Israel is vassal not to a human king but to the divine Suzerain', 'The covenant in Nehemiah 10 is a purely contractual document with no connection to the ancient Near Eastern treaty tradition', 'The suzerainty treaty form was exclusively used for political covenants and was never applied to religious commitments', 'Nehemiah 10 lacks any sanctions or curse element and therefore does not fit the suzerainty treaty pattern', 'a', 'Nehemiah 9:38/10:1 — "we make a sure covenant, and write it" (document), 10:29 — "entered into a curse, and into an oath" (sanctions clause), 10:30-39 — specific stipulations. Scholars such as George Mendenhall and Klaus Baltzer have demonstrated that biblical covenants use the same structural elements as Hittite suzerainty treaties — preamble, historical prologue, stipulations, document clause, witnesses, sanctions.'),
('Nehemiah', 10, 'adults', 8, 'Why does the covenant conclude with "we will not forsake the house of our God" (Neh 10:39) rather than a more comprehensive theological statement, and what does this reveal about the post-exilic community''s central concern?', 'The temple house was the focal point of covenant life — Sabbath, tithes, firstfruits, wood offering, and Levitical support all converge on maintaining God''s dwelling place; to forsake the house was to forsake the covenant itself, so the temple-centred conclusion captures the whole in a single phrase', 'The statement was chosen because the temple treasury was the main practical concern and the theological dimensions were secondary', 'The phrase was chosen to reassure the Persian authorities that the Jews were maintaining their place of worship as required by royal decree', 'The conclusion reveals that the community was primarily concerned with ritual rather than ethical dimensions of covenant faithfulness', 'a', 'Nehemiah 10:39 — "We will not forsake the house of our God." All the specific commitments (vv.30-39) flow toward sustaining the temple: tithes sustain Levites who serve in it, wood keeps its altar burning, firstfruits fill its storerooms. The house of God = the centre of covenant life = the presence of God among his people = everything the exile had taken away.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 11 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 11, 'kids', 1, 'How did the people decide which families would move to live in Jerusalem?', 'They cast lots and one in every ten people was chosen to dwell in Jerusalem', 'Nehemiah chose the strongest families to move to the city', 'Every family agreed to send their firstborn son to live in Jerusalem', 'The king of Persia sent a list of families who were required to live in the holy city', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:1 — "And the rulers of the people dwelt at Jerusalem: the rest of the people also cast lots, to bring one of ten to dwell in Jerusalem the holy city, and nine parts to dwell in other cities."'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'kids', 2, 'What did the rest of the people do for those who willingly offered to dwell in Jerusalem?', 'The people blessed all the men that willingly offered themselves to dwell at Jerusalem', 'They gave them money and food to start their new lives in the city', 'They built new houses for them before they moved in', 'They celebrated a feast in their honour at the temple', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:2 — "And the people blessed all the men, that willingly offered themselves to dwell at Jerusalem."'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'kids', 3, 'Which two tribes are specifically mentioned as dwelling in Jerusalem in Nehemiah 11?', 'The children of Judah and the children of Benjamin', 'The tribe of Levi and the tribe of Simeon', 'The tribe of Ephraim and the tribe of Manasseh', 'The children of Reuben and the children of Gad', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:4 — "And at Jerusalem dwelt certain of the children of Judah, and of the children of Benjamin."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 11, 'teens', 1, 'What title does Nehemiah 11 give to Jerusalem that explains why living there was considered a special calling?', 'The holy city', 'The city of the great king', 'The city of David the servant of God', 'The dwelling place of the LORD of hosts', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:1 — "to dwell in Jerusalem the holy city."'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'teens', 2, 'Who was identified as the leader of the sons of Judah who dwelt at Jerusalem — whose lineage was through Perez?', 'Athaiah the son of Uzziah, son of Zechariah — and the sons of Perez who dwelt at Jerusalem were four hundred threescore and eight valiant men', 'Nehemiah himself who was of the tribe of Judah and dwelt in the governor''s palace', 'Zerubbabel who came from the line of David through Judah', 'Maaseiah the son of Baruch who commanded the men of Judah in Jerusalem', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:4,6 — "And at Jerusalem dwelt certain of the children of Judah...Athaiah the son of Uzziah...Of the sons of Perez; all the sons of Perez that dwelt at Jerusalem were four hundred threescore and eight valiant men."'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'teens', 3, 'What role did the Nethinims (temple servants) play in the resettlement of Jerusalem according to Nehemiah 11?', 'They dwelt in Ophel and the Nethinims dwelt in Ophel unto the water gate eastward and the tower that lieth out', 'They were assigned to guard the outer walls of Jerusalem night and day', 'The Nethinims lived in the valley below the city and served in the temple by day', 'They were given land outside the city in exchange for their service at the altar', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:21 — "But the Nethinims dwelt in Ophel: and Ziha and Gispa were over the Nethinims."'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'teens', 4, 'What was the role of Pethahiah the son of Meshezabeel described at the end of Nehemiah 11?', 'He was at the king''s hand in all matters concerning the people', 'He was the overseer of the Levites who served in the outer courts', 'He was appointed chief scribe to record the names of all who dwelt in Jerusalem', 'He was the treasurer of the temple who collected the tithes from all the cities', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:24 — "And Pethahiah the son of Meshezabeel, of the children of Zerah the son of Judah, was at the king''s hand in all matters concerning the people."'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'teens', 5, 'What were the villages outside Jerusalem that the children of Judah dwelt in according to Nehemiah 11:25-30?', 'Kirjath-arba, Dibon, Jekabzeel, Jeshua, Moladah, Beth-phelet, Hazar-shual, Beer-sheba, and their villages', 'Jericho, Bethel, Gibeon, Ramah, and all the cities of the hill country', 'Hebron, Bethlehem, Engedi, and the cities of the Negeb desert', 'Lachish, Azekah, Makkedah, and all the Shephelah cities', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:25-30 — "And for the villages, with their fields, some of the children of Judah dwelt at Kirjath-arba, and in the villages thereof...at Dibon...at Jekabzeel...Jeshua, and at Moladah, and at Beth-phelet, And at Hazar-shual, and at Beer-sheba, and in the villages thereof."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 1, 'How does the lot-casting in Nehemiah 11:1 reflect biblical theology of divine guidance, and what does the one-in-ten ratio suggest about the demographic challenge facing Jerusalem?', 'Lot-casting (goral) in Israel was understood as a means of discerning God''s will (Proverbs 16:33), not random chance — the one-in-ten ratio reveals that only 10% of the population could be persuaded to leave comfortable village life for the still-vulnerable holy city, quantifying the challenge of urban renewal', 'The lots were a practical administrative tool with no theological significance in the post-exilic period', 'The one-in-ten ratio was a standard Persian military conscription method applied here to civil resettlement', 'Lot-casting was used only when leaders could not agree — here it was a default method because no volunteers came forward', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:1 — "the rest of the people also cast lots, to bring one of ten to dwell in Jerusalem the holy city." Proverbs 16:33 — "The lot is cast into the lap; but the whole disposing thereof is of the LORD." That compulsory lot-casting was needed alongside voluntary offers (v.2) confirms how unpopular urban resettlement was — the city''s walls were new but its safety and infrastructure were still undeveloped.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 2, 'What does the blessing of willing settlers in Nehemiah 11:2 — "the people blessed all the men, that willingly offered themselves to dwell at Jerusalem" — reveal about the community''s values and the nature of sacrifice involved?', 'The communal blessing signals that voluntary service in a dangerous or difficult post was honoured as a form of covenant sacrifice — moving to the underpopulated holy city was a personal cost that deserved public acknowledgment, not just administrative assignment', 'The blessing was a farewell ritual with no special moral significance', 'Those who moved willingly were given financial compensation, and the "blessing" refers to this material reward', 'The blessing indicates the volunteers were regarded as unusually pious, above the spiritual level of the majority', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:2 — "all the men, that willingly offered themselves." The word "willingly" (hithnaddev) uses the same root as Exodus 35:21,29 — the freewill offerings for the tabernacle. Jerusalem was still underpopulated, short of amenities, and potentially a military target — choosing to live there was genuine sacrifice deserving communal honour.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 3, 'How does the inclusion of both Judah and Benjamin in the resettlement of Jerusalem (Neh 11:4-9) reflect the post-exilic community''s self-understanding of being a reunified remnant?', 'Judah and Benjamin were the two southern tribes that survived the Assyrian exile together — their joint presence in Jerusalem represents the continuity of the southern kingdom covenant community and signals that the restoration is not a new Israel but the reconstituted remnant of the old', 'The two tribes are mentioned only because they happened to be the most populous and no theological significance is intended', 'Benjamin''s inclusion was politically necessary since Jerusalem lay on the border of Benjamin''s tribal territory', 'The two tribes represent the priestly and royal lines respectively, making their joint presence a liturgical arrangement', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:4 — "And at Jerusalem dwelt certain of the children of Judah, and of the children of Benjamin." The post-exilic community never claimed to represent all twelve tribes — it consistently identified itself as the surviving remnant of Judah-Benjamin (cf. Ezra 1:5; 4:1; 10:9). Their joint resettlement of Jerusalem mirrors the composition of the pre-exilic southern kingdom.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 4, 'What does the description of the Levitical and temple servant assignments in Nehemiah 11:10-24 reveal about the institutional structure of post-exilic worship?', 'The detailed role assignments — chief priests, Levitical overseers, singers, gatekeepers, Nethinims, and a royal liaison — show a functioning temple bureaucracy with clear lines of authority, specialisation, and royal connection, indicating that post-exilic Judaism had developed a sophisticated institutional worship structure', 'The assignments were temporary and informal, pending the appointment of a legitimate Davidic king to organise worship properly', 'The list indicates that most temple roles were vacant and Nehemiah was struggling to fill basic positions', 'The temple structure described was purely aspirational and not actually implemented during Nehemiah''s governorship', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:11 — "ruler of the house of God"; v.14 — "mighty men of valour" over priests; v.17 — "Mattaniah...the principal to begin the thanksgiving in prayer"; v.22 — "Uzzi...the overseer of the Levites...over the business of the house of God"; v.24 — "Pethahiah...at the king''s hand." The institutional complexity mirrors the pre-exilic temple administration described in 1 Chronicles 23-26.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 5, 'What is the significance of the phrase "the king''s hand" (Neh 11:24) regarding Pethahiah''s role, and what does it reveal about the political situation of post-exilic Judah?', 'It indicates Judah maintained an official Persian liaison — a community representative at the Persian court — confirming that Judah was a recognised provincial entity with channels of communication to the empire, not a forgotten backwater', 'The phrase means Pethahiah was a royal bodyguard assigned to protect the Jewish community from attack', '"At the king''s hand" is a metaphorical expression meaning Pethahiah was faithful and obedient without any political role', 'The phrase indicates Pethahiah had converted to Persian religion and served as a court priest for Artaxerxes', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:24 — "Pethahiah the son of Meshezabeel...was at the king''s hand in all matters concerning the people." The Aramaic term at the background suggests an official intermediary role — a Jewish representative at the Persian court for handling the affairs (dibre) of the people. This confirms that post-exilic Judah was a formally recognised ethno-religious community within the Persian provincial system.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 6, 'How does the village list of Nehemiah 11:25-36 contribute to the book''s theme of the restoration fulfilling the promises of return from exile?', 'The villages of Judah and Benjamin listed stretch from Beer-sheba in the south to the Valley of Craftsmen in the north — demonstrating that the restoration extended well beyond Jerusalem''s walls into the full traditional territory of the two tribes, giving geographic substance to the promise of return', 'The village list is a census document with no thematic significance in the book', 'The list actually reveals how small and geographically restricted the restoration community was compared to the pre-exilic kingdom', 'The villages listed are only those added during Nehemiah''s term and do not represent the earlier returnees'' settlements', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:25-36 — villages extend from Kirjath-arba (Hebron area, south) through Beersheba and its environs (far south) to the valley of craftsmen (northern Benjamin, v.35). Compare Zechariah 8:4-8 — the LORD''s promise that "old men and old women shall dwell in the streets of Jerusalem" and "I will bring them, and they shall dwell in the midst of Jerusalem." The geographic spread shows promise beginning to be fulfilled.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 7, 'What is the theological significance of calling Jerusalem "the holy city" (Neh 11:1,18) in the context of resettlement, and how does this designation function motivationally?', 'The title "holy city" (ir haqodesh) frames residence in Jerusalem as participation in God''s sacred space — it transforms urban relocation from a civic duty into a spiritual vocation, providing the theological motivation for voluntary sacrifice that mere civic duty could not generate', 'The title is a traditional name with no motivational function in the resettlement context', '"Holy city" was an administrative designation used by the Persian authorities to distinguish Jerusalem from other towns', 'The phrase appears only twice and was probably a marginal note that entered the text by copying error', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11:1 — "Jerusalem the holy city" and 11:18 — "all the Levites in the holy city." Isaiah 52:1 — "O Jerusalem, the holy city" uses the same title in the context of restoration from exile. The post-exilic application of Isaiah''s restoration language to the rebuilt Jerusalem interprets the resettlement as the partial fulfilment of Isaiah''s eschatological promises.'),
('Nehemiah', 11, 'adults', 8, 'How does the organisational structure of Nehemiah 11 — governing roles (11:9,14,22), worship roles (11:17,22), service roles (11:21), and political liaison (11:24) — model a vision of redeemed community as a whole society ordered around the presence of God?', 'The chapter presents civic governance, worship leadership, temple service, and political interface all converging on one goal: sustaining the house of God in the holy city — modelling that restoration of community means every dimension of social life structured around the divine presence', 'The chapter is simply a practical administrative record with no theological vision of community embedded in it', 'The different roles show that post-exilic Judaism separated the sacred from the secular more strictly than pre-exilic Israel had done', 'The roles described were temporary emergency appointments that would be replaced when a Davidic king was restored', 'a', 'Nehemiah 11 covers: political leadership (vv.1-3), tribal families (vv.4-9), priests (vv.10-14), Levites/singers/gatekeepers (vv.15-24), village settlements (vv.25-36). The breadth shows that "holy city" encompasses not just the temple but an entire human community — families, politics, worship, economics — all ordered in relation to God''s dwelling. This is the post-exilic prototype of New Testament ecclesiology as the community of God''s presence.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 12 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 12, 'kids', 1, 'What special event happened when the wall of Jerusalem was finished?', 'They had a big celebration to dedicate the wall with singing and thanksgiving', 'They tore it down and rebuilt it', 'They painted it with bright colours', 'They closed the gates forever', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:27 — "And at the dedication of the wall of Jerusalem they sought the Levites out of all their places, to bring them to Jerusalem, to keep the dedication with gladness, both with thanksgivings, and with singing."'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'kids', 2, 'What instruments did they play at the wall dedication?', 'Cymbals, psalteries, and harps', 'Trumpets only', 'Drums and flutes', 'No instruments — just clapping', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:27 — "with cymbals, psalteries, and with harps."'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'kids', 3, 'How many groups of singers marched on top of the wall?', 'Two great companies that gave thanks and marched in opposite directions', 'One large group', 'Three small groups', 'Ten groups of ten people', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:31,38 — "Then I brought up the princes of Judah upon the wall, and appointed two great companies of them that gave thanks."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 12, 'teens', 1, 'Why were the Levites specifically sought out from all their places for the wall dedication?', 'Because they were the appointed musicians and worship leaders — the dedication was a sacred act requiring proper Levitical worship', 'Because they were the strongest workers who built most of the wall', 'Because they were the only literate people who could read the dedication speech', 'Because the law required Levites to inspect all construction projects', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:27 — "they sought the Levites out of all their places, to bring them to Jerusalem, to keep the dedication with gladness." The Levites were scattered in surrounding towns (11:20,36) and had to be specially gathered for their liturgical role.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'teens', 2, 'What did the priests and Levites do before the dedication ceremony?', 'They purified themselves, the people, the gates, and the wall', 'They fasted for seven days', 'They offered burnt offerings only', 'They read the entire law of Moses aloud', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:30 — "And the priests and the Levites purified themselves, and purified the people, and the gates, and the wall."'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'teens', 3, 'Who led one of the two thanksgiving processions on the wall?', 'Ezra the scribe led one procession to the right toward the dung gate', 'Nehemiah led both processions', 'The high priest led both processions', 'The king of Persia sent a representative to lead them', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:36 — "And his brethren...and Ezra the scribe before them."'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'teens', 4, 'What happened at the end of the dedication when both processions met at the temple?', 'They offered great sacrifices and rejoiced so loudly that the joy of Jerusalem was heard afar off', 'They sat down quietly and prayed', 'They closed the gates and went home', 'They appointed new leaders for each section of the wall', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:43 — "Also that day they offered great sacrifices, and rejoiced: for God had made them rejoice with great joy...so that the joy of Jerusalem was heard even afar off."'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'teens', 5, 'What provisions were made for the singers and gatekeepers after the dedication?', 'Men were appointed to oversee storerooms for the portions assigned to the Levites, singers, and gatekeepers by the law', 'They were given permanent houses inside the temple courts', 'They were exempted from all future taxes by the Persian king', 'They were sent back to their villages with no ongoing support', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:44 — "And at that time were some appointed over the chambers for the treasures, for the offerings, for the firstfruits, and for the tithes, to gather into them out of the fields of the cities the portions of the law for the priests and Levites."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 1, 'How does the two-procession structure of the wall dedication in Nehemiah 12:31-43 function as a theological statement about the nature of the rebuilt community?', 'The two companies marching in opposite directions around the wall and converging at the temple creates a visual encirclement of the holy city — symbolically claiming the entire perimeter for God and centering the community''s identity on the house of God as its convergence point', 'The two processions were a practical solution for the large number of participants rather than a theological arrangement', 'The processions followed standard Persian civic dedication protocols that had no religious significance', 'The two groups represented the two tribes of Judah and Benjamin and marched to their respective ancestral territories', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:31,38,40 — two companies go "to the right" and "over against them" and both "stood still in the house of God." The convergence at the temple parallels the design of the tabernacle camp (Numbers 2) where all Israel surrounded and faced God''s dwelling. The dedication procession enacts the theology that the wall exists to protect the sacred center.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 2, 'What is the significance of the purification of the wall and gates (Neh 12:30) in light of the holiness theology of the Pentateuch?', 'Purifying inanimate structures extends the holiness category beyond persons and sacred objects to the civic infrastructure itself — the wall is not merely a military fortification but a boundary of sacred space, requiring ritual consecration like the tabernacle in Exodus 40', 'Purification of walls was a standard ancient Near Eastern construction custom with no distinctively Israelite theology', 'The purification was a symbolic gesture acknowledging that sin had been committed during the building process', 'Wall purification was required only because foreign labourers had touched the stones during construction', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:30 — "the priests and the Levites purified themselves, and purified the people, and the gates, and the wall." Exodus 40:9-11 records the anointing of the tabernacle and its furnishings. The extension of purification ritual to the city wall treats Jerusalem''s fortifications as the boundary of sacred space — a theological concept later developed in Zechariah 2:5 where God himself is a "wall of fire round about."'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 3, 'How does the phrase "the joy of Jerusalem was heard even afar off" (Neh 12:43) connect to the earlier narrative of Ezra 3:13 and what does this literary echo signify?', 'Ezra 3:13 records that at the temple foundation "the noise was heard afar off" — but that sound mixed weeping with joy; now at the wall dedication the sound "afar off" is pure joy, signifying that the restoration has progressed from ambiguous grief-mixed-with-hope to full-throated celebration', 'The phrase is a stock expression for loud celebrations and has no intentional connection to Ezra 3', 'Both passages describe the same event from different perspectives rather than sequential events', 'The "afar off" hearing is meant to describe the reaction of hostile neighbouring peoples rather than celebrating Jews', 'a', 'Ezra 3:13 — "the noise was heard afar off" (weeping + joy); Nehemiah 12:43 — "the joy of Jerusalem was heard even afar off" (pure joy). The deliberate echo creates a narrative arc: the incomplete, tear-laden celebration of the foundation has matured into unambiguous rejoicing at the completed wall — the restoration has moved from promise to fulfilment.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 4, 'What does the genealogical list of priests and Levites in Nehemiah 12:1-26 contribute to the book''s theological argument about legitimacy and continuity?', 'The priestly genealogy spanning from Zerubbabel''s return through Joiakim to Eliashib and beyond establishes an unbroken chain of legitimate worship leadership — proving that the post-exilic community is the authentic continuation of pre-exilic Israel, not a new religious movement', 'The list is a bureaucratic record included for archival completeness with no theological argument', 'The genealogy was added by a later editor and disrupts the original flow of the dedication narrative', 'The priestly list is included to show how many positions remained unfilled and thus how incomplete the restoration was', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:1 — "these are the priests and the Levites that went up with Zerubbabel" through v.26 — "these were in the days of Joiakim...and Nehemiah the governor, and of Ezra the priest, the scribe." The four-generation chain (Jeshua→Joiakim→Eliashib→contemporaries) demonstrates institutional continuity across nearly a century of restored worship.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 5, 'How does the appointment of the Davidic praise model in Nehemiah 12:24,45-46 connect to the Chronicler''s theology of worship?', 'The explicit reference to David''s command for antiphonal praise and the mention of Asaph as the historical founder of the singers connects post-exilic worship directly to the Davidic liturgical tradition — the restored community is not inventing new worship but reviving the authentic Davidic pattern', 'David is mentioned merely as a historical figure without any normative theological function', 'The reference to David was added to give the rebuilt temple legitimacy it otherwise lacked', 'Asaph and David are mentioned because their compositions were the only hymns available', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:24 — "to praise and to give thanks, according to the commandment of David the man of God"; v.46 — "in the days of David and Asaph of old there were chief of the singers." 1 Chronicles 25:1 records David''s original appointment of Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun. Nehemiah presents Davidic worship as the normative standard that post-exilic practice must faithfully reproduce.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 6, 'What does the people''s joyful giving of priestly and Levitical portions in Nehemiah 12:44,47 reveal about the spiritual health of the community at this moment?', 'Willing financial support for temple personnel indicates a community that values worship as central to its identity — this generous moment contrasts with the neglect Nehemiah will confront in chapter 13, making the dedication a high-water mark of communal faithfulness', 'Regular tithes were compulsory under Persian law and voluntary compliance indicates nothing about spiritual health', 'The people gave generously only because Nehemiah was personally supervising the collections', 'The tithe system was newly instituted by Nehemiah, so this represents a first payment rather than willing generosity', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:44 — "for Judah rejoiced for the priests and for the Levites that waited"; v.47 — "all Israel in the days of Zerubbabel, and in the days of Nehemiah, gave the portions of the singers and the porters." This willing provision stands in sharp contrast to 13:10 where Levites fled because their portions were not given — the dedication chapter captures a moment of ideal community that proves fragile.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 7, 'How does Nehemiah 12:45 describe the role of temple singers and gatekeepers as keeping "the ward of their God, and the ward of the purification"?', 'The term "ward" (mishmereth) frames worship ministry as a military-style guard duty — the singers and gatekeepers are sentinels of holiness, maintaining the boundary between sacred and common that defines Israel''s covenant relationship with a holy God', 'The "ward" language is purely bureaucratic and refers to shift schedules for temple workers', 'Singers and gatekeepers were literally armed guards who protected the temple from physical threats', 'The purification ward refers specifically to the water purification system they maintained for the temple', 'a', 'Nehemiah 12:45 — "the singers and the porters kept the ward of their God, and the ward of the purification." The term mishmereth (Numbers 3:7-8; 1 Chronicles 23:32) consistently describes sacred custodial responsibility — the Levites "keep charge" of the sanctuary. Applied to singers and gatekeepers, it elevates their worship roles to the status of sacred guardianship.'),
('Nehemiah', 12, 'adults', 8, 'How does the wall dedication in Nehemiah 12 function as the narrative and theological climax of the book?', 'The dedication brings together every thread: the completed wall (ch.1-6), the reconstituted community (ch.7-11), the worship leadership (ch.12:1-26), and the Torah-centered liturgy (ch.8) — all converging in a celebration that enacts the book''s central vision of a holy city with a holy people serving a holy God, before the sobering anticlimax of chapter 13', 'The wall dedication is simply one event among many and chapter 13 is the true climax', 'The dedication is anticlimactic because Nehemiah does not personally lead either procession', 'The genealogical lists that precede the dedication undermine its function as a climax by slowing the narrative', 'a', 'The dedication (12:27-47) resolves every narrative tension: the wall Sanballat mocked (4:1-3) is finished; the community that struggled with internal oppression (5:1-5) gives joyfully; the worship that was neglected (13:10-11) functions at full strength. That chapter 13 follows with reforms against backsliding makes the dedication a peak from which decline is measured — the pattern of Judges applied to the post-exilic era.');

-- ═══ Nehemiah Chapter 13 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Nehemiah', 13, 'kids', 1, 'What did Nehemiah find when he came back to Jerusalem after being away?', 'The priest Eliashib had given Tobiah a room inside the temple where offerings were supposed to be stored', 'Everything was perfect and everyone was obeying God', 'The wall had fallen down again', 'The temple had been destroyed', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:7 — "I came to Jerusalem, and understood of the evil that Eliashib did for Tobiah, in preparing him a chamber in the courts of the house of God."'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'kids', 2, 'What did Nehemiah do about the Sabbath day?', 'He shut the gates of Jerusalem before the Sabbath so no buying and selling would happen', 'He let everyone do whatever they wanted', 'He made the Sabbath last two days instead of one', 'He cancelled the Sabbath', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:19 — "I commanded that the gates should be shut, and charged that they should not be opened till after the sabbath."'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'kids', 3, 'What problem did Nehemiah find with some of the Jewish children?', 'Their children spoke other languages and could not speak the language of Judah', 'They were all very well-behaved', 'They refused to eat their food', 'They had run away from home', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:24 — "And their children spake half in the speech of Ashdod, and could not speak in the Jews'' language."'),
-- Teens
('Nehemiah', 13, 'teens', 1, 'Why had the Levites left the temple and gone back to their fields?', 'Because the people had stopped giving tithes, so the Levites had no food and had to farm to survive', 'Because they were tired of serving in the temple', 'Because the high priest sent them away', 'Because a new law required all men to farm', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:10 — "And I perceived that the portions of the Levites had not been given them: for the Levites and the singers, that did the work, were fled every one to his field."'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'teens', 2, 'What did Nehemiah physically do when he confronted the men who had married foreign wives?', 'He contended with them, cursed them, smote certain of them, and plucked off their hair', 'He quietly asked them to change their ways', 'He wrote them a letter of warning', 'He banished them from the city permanently', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:25 — "And I contended with them, and cursed them, and smote certain of them, and plucked off their hair, and made them swear by God."'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'teens', 3, 'What Old Testament example did Nehemiah use to warn against foreign marriages?', 'King Solomon, who was led into sin by his foreign wives despite being the wisest man', 'King David, who married Bathsheba', 'Abraham, who took Hagar as a wife', 'Moses, who married a Midianite woman', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:26 — "Did not Solomon king of Israel sin by these things?...even him did outlandish women cause to sin."'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'teens', 4, 'Who was the grandson of the high priest that Nehemiah chased away?', 'A son-in-law of Sanballat the Horonite — one of Eliashib''s grandsons had married Sanballat''s daughter', 'A servant of Tobiah the Ammonite', 'A messenger from the king of Persia', 'A false prophet named Shemaiah', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:28 — "And one of the sons of Joiada, the son of Eliashib the high priest, was son in law to Sanballat the Horonite: therefore I chased him from me."'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'teens', 5, 'What is the repeated prayer that Nehemiah prays throughout chapter 13?', '"Remember me, O my God, for good" — he asks God to remember his faithful actions', 'He asks God to destroy all his enemies', 'He asks God to send fire from heaven', 'He asks God to make him king of Israel', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:14,22,31 — "Remember me, O my God, concerning this, and wipe not out my good deeds." And v.31 — "Remember me, O my God, for good."'),
-- Adults
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 1, 'How does Nehemiah 13 function as a deliberate anticlimax after the wall dedication of chapter 12, and what theological purpose does this literary structure serve?', 'The rapid descent from joyful dedication to covenant violation mirrors the golden calf incident after Sinai (Exodus 32) — both show that external religious celebrations cannot sustain covenant faithfulness, pointing to the need for internal transformation that only the new covenant can provide', 'Chapter 13 describes minor administrative issues that do not significantly diminish the achievements of chapters 1-12', 'The anticlimax is an artifact of editorial arrangement and was not intended by the original author', 'Chapter 13 describes events that occurred before the dedication but were placed after it for chronological correction', 'a', 'The pattern of celebration→violation (ch.12→13) deliberately echoes Exodus 24:7-11→32:1 (covenant meal→golden calf) and Joshua 24:24-25→Judges 2:10-12 (covenant→apostasy). Nehemiah''s book ends not with triumph but with "remember me" — the reformer knows his work is fragile and only God''s remembrance can secure it.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 2, 'What does the Tobiah-in-the-temple-chamber incident (Neh 13:4-9) reveal about the relationship between political compromise and spiritual corruption?', 'Eliashib the priest gave Tobiah — a political enemy of the restoration who had opposed the wall-building — a chamber in the sacred space where offerings were stored, showing how political alliances with those who oppose God''s purposes inevitably lead to the displacement of worship priorities', 'Tobiah''s use of the chamber was a minor administrative matter since the storeroom was not part of the sacred temple space', 'Eliashib was forced by Persian authorities to accommodate Tobiah and had no choice in the matter', 'Tobiah had converted to Judaism and his presence in the temple was legitimate under the law', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:4-5 — "Eliashib the priest...was allied unto Tobiah: And he had prepared for him a great chamber, where aforetime they laid the meat offerings." Tobiah was an Ammonite (2:10,19; 4:3,7) who actively opposed the wall. His installation in the temple storeroom physically displaced the sacred offerings — a spatial metaphor for how political accommodation pushes worship to the margins.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 3, 'How does the tithe crisis of Nehemiah 13:10-13 connect to Malachi''s contemporary prophecy, and what does this reveal about the post-exilic spiritual condition?', 'Malachi 3:8-10 ("Will a man rob God?...in tithes and offerings") addresses the identical crisis from the prophetic perspective — together they confirm that neglect of Levitical support was not an isolated incident but a systemic failure reflecting the community''s declining commitment to covenant obligations', 'Malachi and Nehemiah address different time periods and the similarity is coincidental', 'The tithe crisis was caused by economic hardship under Persian taxation, not spiritual decline', 'Malachi''s tithe prophecy is addressed to priests, not the laity, so it covers a different issue', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:10 — Levites "fled every one to his field"; Malachi 3:8 — "Will a man rob God? Yet ye have robbed me...in tithes and offerings." The convergence of narrative (Nehemiah) and prophetic (Malachi) testimony confirms a broad-based covenant failure — the post-exilic community that promised faithfulness (10:37-39) quickly defaulted.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 4, 'What is the theological significance of Nehemiah''s Sabbath enforcement (13:15-22), particularly his reference to the exile as a consequence of Sabbath violation?', 'Nehemiah explicitly connects Sabbath-breaking to the cause of the exile (v.18), making Sabbath observance a litmus test of whether the restored community has learned from its past — repeating the violation that caused exile risks repeating the punishment', 'Nehemiah''s Sabbath enforcement was a personal preference without direct connection to exile theology', 'The Sabbath rules were new regulations Nehemiah invented that had no precedent in the Torah', 'Nehemiah was enforcing Persian market regulations that happened to coincide with the Sabbath', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:17-18 — "What evil thing is this that ye do, and profane the sabbath day? Did not your fathers thus, and did not our God bring all this evil upon us, and upon this city? yet ye bring more wrath upon Israel by profaning the sabbath." Compare Jeremiah 17:21-27, which explicitly warned that Sabbath violation would result in Jerusalem''s destruction. Nehemiah sees post-exilic Sabbath-breaking as courting a second exile.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 5, 'How does Nehemiah''s violent reaction to intermarriage (13:25 — smiting, hair-pulling) compare with Ezra''s response (Ezra 9:3 — self-abasement), and what do these contrasting approaches reveal?', 'Ezra directed his grief inward (tearing his own hair and garments), while Nehemiah directed his anger outward (striking offenders and pulling their hair) — together they represent the full spectrum of godly response to covenant violation: prophetic self-identification with communal sin and governmental enforcement of covenant standards', 'Nehemiah''s violence shows he was less spiritual than Ezra who responded with prayer', 'Both responses were equally inappropriate for leaders and reflect personal temperament rather than theology', 'Ezra''s response was earlier and gentler because the problem was less severe; Nehemiah''s was later and harsher because the situation had worsened', 'a', 'Ezra 9:3 — "I rent my garment and my mantle, and plucked off the hair of my head and of my beard" (self-directed grief); Nehemiah 13:25 — "I contended with them, and cursed them, and smote certain of them, and plucked off their hair" (other-directed discipline). The contrast is not superiority but complementary roles: Ezra as priest intercedes; Nehemiah as governor enforces.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 6, 'What does Nehemiah''s expulsion of Eliashib''s grandson who married Sanballat''s daughter (13:28) reveal about the intersection of priestly purity and political alliance in post-exilic Judah?', 'The marriage united the high priestly family with the chief political opponent of Jerusalem''s restoration — Nehemiah saw this as a deliberate attempt to compromise the priestly line from within, making expulsion not merely personal discipline but defense of the entire restoration project', 'The expulsion was motivated by personal animosity between Nehemiah and Sanballat rather than theological principle', 'The priest''s marriage to a Samaritan woman was acceptable under Torah law; Nehemiah acted beyond his authority', 'Josephus identifies this expelled priest as the founder of the Samaritan temple on Mount Gerizim, but this connection is historically unreliable', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:28 — "one of the sons of Joiada, the son of Eliashib the high priest, was son in law to Sanballat the Horonite: therefore I chased him from me." The marriage would have given Sanballat — who had mocked (4:1-2) and plotted against (6:1-14) the restoration — influence over the high priesthood itself. Josephus (Ant. 11.7.2) connects this expulsion to the founding of the Samaritan temple, making it a watershed moment.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 7, 'How do Nehemiah''s four "remember me" prayers (13:14,22,29,31) function as a theological commentary on the limits of human reform?', 'The repeated appeals to God''s remembrance rather than to the community''s gratitude reveal that Nehemiah recognises his reforms are fragile and dependent not on human enforcement but on divine preservation — the reformer knows that only God can sustain what human effort has built', 'The prayers are formulaic memorial inscriptions common in ancient Near Eastern building projects', 'The prayers reveal Nehemiah''s insecurity and desire for personal recognition rather than theological insight', 'The four prayers correspond to the four reforms and serve as chapter dividers rather than theological statements', 'a', 'Nehemiah 13:14 — "Remember me, O my God, concerning this"; v.22 — "Remember me, O my God, concerning this also"; v.29 — "Remember them, O my God, because they have defiled the priesthood"; v.31 — "Remember me, O my God, for good." The shift from "remember me" (positive) to "remember them" (negative) and back to "remember me" reveals a man caught between hope and realism — trusting God''s remembrance rather than human constancy.'),
('Nehemiah', 13, 'adults', 8, 'How does the book of Nehemiah as a whole — ending with the reforms of chapter 13 rather than the celebration of chapter 12 — present a theology of restoration that is honest about its incompleteness?', 'Ending with ongoing reform rather than completed triumph honestly acknowledges that the exile''s root cause (covenant unfaithfulness) has not been finally resolved — the community keeps repeating the same sins (intermarriage, tithe neglect, Sabbath-breaking) that the prophets condemned, pointing beyond human reform to the divine solution of Jeremiah 31:33 and Ezekiel 36:26', 'The ending is simply chronological and carries no intentional theological message about completeness', 'Chapter 13 was a later addition and the book originally ended triumphantly at chapter 12', 'The reforms of chapter 13 are successful and the book ends on a positive note of corrected behaviour', 'a', 'The book''s structure — wall built (1-6), community restored (7-12), community fails again (13) — mirrors the Deuteronomistic cycle of grace→obligation→failure→grace. Nehemiah''s final "remember me, O my God, for good" (13:31) leaves the last word not with human achievement but with divine mercy — the only foundation that can sustain what human hands have built.');
